In the Dunes
Eastbound CSX M326 runs daily from Chicago Barr Yard to Grand Rapids, Michigan. The train is seen on the former Pere Marquette to Grand Rapids. The lead engine CSX 5433 GE ES44DC with CSX 5456 GE ES44DC trailing.  This is a long manifest freight with a wide variety of rolling stock.

The 136-mile CSX Grand Rapids Subdivision is the former Pere Marquette Railroad (Chesapeake & Ohio Railway - Chicago Subdivision). Originally constructed in 1870-1872 from New Buffalo to Grand Rapids by Chicago & Michigan Lake Shore Railroad then extended to Porter Indiana in 1903. Trackage rights have always been used west of Porter on the former New York Central line, as far as Pine Junction where it rejoins the former B&O.

Empire Builder
The Empire Builder is an Amtrak long-distance passenger train that operates daily between Chicago and either Seattle or Portland via two sections west of Spokane.

The Amtrak Train 7 is seen approaching the Olympic Sculpture Park in Seattle, Washington. Taken at 11:28 Pacific Time, it has two miles to go for a 11:29 scheduled arrival time.

The train has traveled 2,206 miles from Chicago. The trip normally takes 46 hours and 10 minutes.

Urban Canyon
A BNSF light engine move repositioning three locomotives passes northbound through downtown Seattle.  A light engine move refers to taking an engine from here to there without a train.  BNSF 8778 EMD SD70ACe is on point with BNSF 5440 GE C44-9W and BNSF 6961 GE ES44C4 trailing.

After exiting the North Portal of the railroad tunnel under Seattle, the mainline winds through a narrow path between buildings before emerging onto the waterfront. There, the line follows Elliot Bay for three miles north to BNSF Balmer Yard.

The Great Northern Tunnel is a 1-mile double-tracked railway tunnel under downtown Seattle, Washington. It was completed by the Great Northern Railway in 1905, now part of the BNSF Scenic Subdivision.  The BNSF Scenic Sub railroad line runs about 155 miles from Seattle to Wenatchee, Washington. It is part of the BNSF Northern Transcon that runs from Chicago to Seattle.

More Locomotives in Winter
Amtrak Empire Builder passes along the Seattle waterfront, running an hour and a half late due to heavy snow.

After traveling from Chicago to Spokane, Washington, the Amtrak Empire Builder splits into two trains. Train 7 continues on to Seattle as a shortened consist, and the cars that split off become Train 27 to Portland.

Normally the train has two locomotives, with one going to Portland and one to Seattle after the section split in Spokane. Today the train had three locomotives, so two are on the section to Seattle.

BNSF requires Amtrak trains on the Empire Builder route in winter have three operating locomotives in the mountains when temperatures are dangerously cold. Failure of Head End Power (HEP) in a single locomotive could be dangerous for passengers and crew. 

Only one unit can supply HEP at a time. Since the 480V power cables pass through each locomotive, any locomotive can be set up as the HEP generator to supply heat and power to the passenger cars.

Quintessential Seattle Railfanning
A BNSF crew passes the Seattle Olympic Sculpture Park with a single Boeing 7373 fuselage coming from BNSF Balmer Yard to the Boeing plant in Renton, Washington. The Seattle Space Needle is visible in the background.

In 2005, Boeing sold its Wichita division and Oklahoma operations to Spirit.  Today, they manufacture a significant part of the 737 fuselage, and BNSF transports them for final assembly to Washington State.

At the Boeing final assembly plant in Renton, the wings, fuselage and landing gear are married together, as well as avionics and interiors are installed as it moves down the assembly line. As of April 2015, the two 737 production lines produce 42 planes per month or 2 planes per day. It takes 9 days from the time an empty shell arrives at the factory until a completed plane roles out the door ready to fly to the paint shop. Issues with the pandemic and the 737 Max program have caused some production challenges in the interim.

Fuselage on Flatcar
A special move by BNSF passes the Seattle Olympic Sculpture Park with a single Boeing 7373 fuselage coming from BNSF Balmer Yard to the Boeing plant in Renton, Washington. In February 2018, BNSF delivered 10,000th fuselage to Renton by rail. A completed Boeing 737 sells for over $100 million dollars, so this is a very high value load. BNSF 3035 EMD GP40X is on point with BNSF 2731 EMD GP39-2 trailing pulling the two-flatcar train.

In 2005, Boeing sold its Wichita division and Oklahoma operations to Spirit.  Today, they manufacture a significant part of the 737 fuselage, and BNSF transports them around 1,800 miles for final assembly to Washington State. At the Boeing final assembly plant in Renton, the wings, fuselage and landing gear are married together, as well as avionics and interiors are installed as it moves down the assembly line.

Empty Trash Train
Empty garbage containers pass Carkeek Park in Seattle in 2016. Garbage from Northwestern Washington State is transported by BNSF in intermodal containers. Garbage loads are trucked into Delta Yard at Everett, Washington. The garbage filled containers are transported to Allied Waste landfill at Roosevelt, Washington in 6,000 foot trains.

BNSF 4096 GE C44-9W is on point with BNSF 7613 GE ES44DC trailing.  For over 30 years BNSF and Union Pacific have been operating garbage trains from the greater Seattle. At Roosevelt the containers are unloaded and trucked a few miles to the landfill. After unloading at Roosevelt, the empties head back to Seattle.

In The City
A BNSF light engine move repositioning two locomotives passes northbound through downtown Seattle. A light engine move refers to taking an engine from here to there without a train. BNSF 5362 GE C44-9W is on point with BNSF 5981 GE ES44AC trailing.
 
After exiting the North Portal of the railroad tunnel under Seattle, the mainline winds through a narrow path between buildings before emerging onto the waterfront. An intermodal yard is just a bit south of the tunnel, so it is not unusual to see power heading to and from the service facilities in Balmer Yard.

BNSF Interbay Facilities 
North of Balmer Yard are the car shops (left to right), diesel shop, roundhouse and fueling facility and sand towers. Behind the shops are Salmon Bay, the Ballard Locks and Puget Sound. 

The railroad roundhouse is nearing extinction in Washington State. BNSF demolished the former NP Pasco roundhouse, leaving the BNSF Interbay Roundhouse in Ballard. Built in 1929 for the Great Northern Railway, Interbay has a 112 foot turntable and 15 stalls, 16 if you include the machine shop. The roundhouse is currently being utilized as the BNSF Interbay Locomotive Facility, used for the heavy repairs of BNSF diesels. In addition to the roundhouse, there is a diesel house, where multiple level ramps allow workers access to every part of a locomotive. Across the mainline is the BNSF Interbay Car Shop. The sand towers at the fueling facility are notable feature, and are visible from the neighborhoods.

Great Northern at Interbay 
The Interbay neighborhood in Seattle, Washington is in a valley between Queen Anne Hill on the east and Magnolia on the west, plus filled-in areas of Smith Cove and Salmon Bay. Much of Interbay’s land is used by BNSF Railway's Balmer Yard and BNSF Interbay Shops. In 1884 the Seattle, Lake Shore and Eastern Railway purchased all but 50 acres in Interbay and built a north–south rail line through the area. The Great Northern Railway later acquired control of the railway and constructed Interbay yard and shops. GN also developed two new coal and lumber piers, today's Piers 90 and 91, increasing industrialization of Interbay. During the 1911–1916 construction of the Lake Washington Ship Canal the Port of Seattle built Fishermen's Terminal on Salmon Bay at the north end of Interbay. Today Fisherman’s Terminal is the home port for Seattle's commercial fishing fleet. Fisherman's Terminal is home to some of the vessels in the Discovery Channel TV series Deadliest Catch.

Locomotives and Cruise Ships
The Interbay neighborhood in Seattle, Washington is in a valley between Queen Anne Hill on the east and Magnolia on the west, plus filled-in areas of Smith Cove and Salmon Bay. Much of Interbay’s land is used by BNSF Railway's Balmer Yard and BNSF Interbay Shops. A cruise ship is seen in the background at Smith Cove Cruise Terminal at Pier 91. The locomotives are parked in front of BNSF Balmer Yard offices. The yard was built by Great Northern Railway as Interbay Yard. As part of a modernization in the late 1960s, it was renamed after former GN vice president Thomas Balmer. The nearby engine servicing area is still known as Interbay.

BNSF Interbay Car Shop
In Balmer Yard, BNSF has a freight car repair facility that diagnose, adjust, repair, or overhaul railroad rolling stock.

A “bad order” freight car refers to a rail car requiring repairs before it is unloaded or loaded. Common freight car issues include repair to running gear or safety appliances. Examples are wheels, trucks, brakes, air hoses, draft gear, couplers, ladders, and platforms. Coupler repair is one of the more common reasons for bad orders. Couplers may require a complete change out, or sometimes just the coupler knuckle, which is the part that moves in the center of the coupler. Couplers receive some of the hardest wear and tear on a railcar.

In the first 11 months of 2022, railroads moved more carloads of chemicals than in any comparable period in history; more carloads of food products than any year since 2012; the fourth-highest carloads of grain since 2009; and the second-highest carloads of iron and steel scrap since 2014. Around 1/3 of U.S. exports move by rail.

BNSF Balmer Mini Hump 
The “Mini-Hump” yard backs up to Smith Cove Cruise Terminal at Pier 91 and Pier 90 commercial moorage.  During World War II, these piers were large naval supply depots used to supply needed war materiel to Alaska and the Pacific. The yards played an important role in transporting goods to the supply depots.
 
The small classification yard at BNSF Balmer Yard is the smallest hump yard on BNSF, with just 16 short tracks in the bowl. Originally a single mechanical retarder controlled the descent of cars but was removed in 1994. It was replaced with hydraulic plungers that are attached to the inside of the rails similar to what UP uses at Roseville. Overall, the yard is over 80 acres and has 41 parallel tracks. The Interbay (Seattle) mini-hump was built by Great Northern in 1960. It has been used on and off as various BNSF management has tried to optimize operations. Balmer is not a part of the major BNSF classification yards. In all, BNSF has eight major hump yards that use gravity to sort rail cars and build trains.

BNSF Pasco Hump Yard
Pasco was a railroad town from the beginning when Northern Pacific (NP) Railway’s named the town in 1881. The Spokane, Portland & Seattle Railway (SP&S)was completed from Pasco to Portland along the Columbia River in 1908 and the line was opened from Spokane to Pasco in 1909.

Pasco became home to the first electronic freight classification hump yard in the Pacific Northwest in 1955. Classification yards are where railroad cars are separated into blocks of cars headed for individual destinations. These blocks are combined to form new trains.

A hump yard is inclined on both ends. When cars are mechanically released, they roll down the tracks into the proper section. The new $5.5 million hump yard provided faster handling of increased traffic from the Columbia Basin agricultural business.

NP and SP&S merged into Burlington Northern in 1970.  In 1996 Atchison, Topeka & Santa Fe Railway merged with BN to become Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway, now BNSF Railway. More than 400 BNSF employees work in Pasco. BNSF’s Pasco yard is one of eight BNSF hump yards vital to the movement of over 1.5 million carloads of freight each year.

Every Day is Hump Day
BNSF’s operates eight hump yards vital to the movement of over 1.5 million carloads of freight each year. Hump yards, also known as classification yards, are where railroad cars are separated into blocks of cars headed for individual destinations. These blocks are combined to form new trains.

Classification yards are comprised of three parts: the receiving yard, the classification bowl, and the departure yard.

A manifest train carrying mixed freight enters the receiving area. The cars to be sorted are pushed up a small hill (hump) on the lead track. At the crest of the hump, a single car or a block of cars intended for a specific destination track are uncoupled from the train by a yard worker. Gravity propels the car or block of cars into the classification bowl, which directs cars to tracks assigned to destinations. Each of the bowl tracks represent a destination. In the departure yard, blocks of sorted cars are assembled into trains. 

In 2018, BNSF completed a multi-year project that modernized hump yard operations by implementing Terminal Process Control (TPC) technology. TPC has been installed at all eight BNSF hump yards:
• Barstow, California
• Galesburg, Illinois
• Kansas City, Kansas
• Lincoln, Nebraska
• Memphis; Tennessee
• Minneapolis, Minnesota
• Pasco, Washington
• Tulsa, Oklahoma.

Commemorative
Amtrak Commemorative Operation Lifesaver 50th Anniversary Locomotive (AMTK 203) is on point of the Amtrak Empire Builder as is passes along Elliot Bay in Seattle, Washington. The Locomotive is a specially-painted Amtrak P-42 diesel locomotive, emblazoned on both sides with the message, “See Tracks? The Empire Builder is an Amtrak long-distance passenger train that operates daily between Chicago and either Seattle or Portland via two sections west of Spokane. After traveling from Chicago to Spokane, Washington, the Amtrak Empire Builder splits into two trains. Train 7 continues on to Seattle as a shorten consist, and cars that split off become Train 27 to Portland. The Amtrak Train 7 has traveled 2206 miles from Chicago on a trip normally takes 46 hours and 10 minutes.

North Portal
After exiting the North Portal of the railroad tunnel under Seattle, the mainline winds through a narrow path between buildings before emerging onto the waterfront. There, the line follows Elliot Bay for three miles north to BNSF Balmer Yard. The North Portal control point is a universal crossover allowing the BNSF dispatchers flexibility on track assignments in this dense urban area of Seattle.
 
The Great Northern Tunnel is a 1-mile double-tracked railway tunnel under downtown Seattle, Washington. It was completed by the Great Northern Railway in 1905, now part of the BNSF Scenic Subdivision. The BNSF Scenic Sub railroad line runs about 155 miles from Seattle to Wenatchee, Washington. It is part of the BNSF Northern Transcon that runs from Chicago to Seattle.
 
A BNSF light engine move of three locomotives passes northbound along the Seattle waterfront, and is about to pass under the Olympic Sculpture Garden. A light engine move refers to taking an engine from here to there without a train. BNSF 8778 EMD SD70ACe is on point with BNSF 5440 GE C44-9W and BNSF 6961 GE ES44C4 trailing.
 
“Seattle Cloud Cover” (2004) by artist Teresita Fernández spans across the edge of the Olympic Sculpture Park bridge over the railroad tracks, visible above the train. Fernández’s glass bridge invites viewers to look through saturated color photographs, sandwiched in glass.

CABLESS
BNSF 343 EMD GP60B is seen here on a northbound manifest freight in Seattle. BNSF 343 was built in 8/1991 as ATSF 343, a "Super Fleet" GP60B delivered in red and silver warbonnet paint. Santa Fe 325–347 were the only GP60Bs. Some of these remain in service with BNSF.
 
Up until the 1950s, B Units were common with streamlined locomotives. By the 1950s B units declined as railroads began purchasing more road-switchers with cabs as trailing power. In the 1990's Santa Fe and Burlington Northern purchased cabless versions of EMD and GE locomotives, and B units returned once again.
 
Cabless diesel locomotives do not have a crew cab built and serves as a "booster" in a consist providing more horse-power for the leading locomotive. The lead locomotive uses Multiple Unit Control via a MU Cable between the engines that uses 27 pins to pass electrical signals for throttle positions, dynamic braking, head lights, sanders, MU engine shutdown among others.
 
EMD GP60 series is a 4-axle (B-B) diesel-electric locomotive built by General Motors Electro-Motive Division between 1985 and 1994. A total of 294 GP60, 23 GP60B and 63 GP60M units were built by EMD. GP60 were standard cab, GP60M had wide nose Safety Cabs, and Cabless 'B' units of this locomotive model were known as GP60B models. The GP 60 series were the last of the EMD “Geeps” built.

BNSF SEATTLE MAINLINE
North of King Street station in Seattle is the 155 miles long BNSF Scenic Subdivision (Seattle-Everett-Wenatchee). LORAM RAILVAC
Seen in downtown Seattle just after exiting the North Portal of the Great Northern Tunnel.
 
The Loram LRV is a rail-mounted specialty excavating machine that removes up to 50 cubic yards of material per hour using mechanical agitation and airflow. It is capable of excavating a host of material including compacted or ice-crusted ballast, mud, water, sand and soil. The Railvac has 5,000 pounds of force to break up tough material. It is ideal for areas with restricted clearances.
 
BNSF was using the machine to perform maintenance on the roadbed within the mile long Great Northern Tunnel that runs under downtown Seattle. A BNSF Hi-Rail pick-up truck escorted the device to assure safe operation. After filling the device with dirt, ballast and debris, it dumped the excavated material near the Olympic Sculpture Park along the tracks so it could be hauled away.

Ferromex is a private rail consortium that operates the largest  railway in Mexico with combined mileage (Ferromex + Ferrosur) of 7,500 miles. The names is an abbreviation of Ferrocarril Mexicano or "Mexican Railway". It is considered a 
North American Class I railroad. Ferromex emerged in 1998 as a result of the privatization of government-owned railways by then President of Mexico Ernesto Zedillo Ponce de León. In 2005, Grupo México, owner of Ferromex, purchased Infraestructura y Transportes Ferroviarios, the parent company of Ferrosur. Union Pacific owns a 26% stake in Ferrocarril Mexicano, or Ferromex. Between about 1995 and 2014, rail-moved freight traffic volume in Mexico doubled.

NSC 6000 Gondola
AIMX 20193 seen in BNSF Balmer Yard in Seattle, Washington. Athearn recently announced models of the NSC 6000 and NSC6400 in HO and N scale that are slated to ship in 2024.
 
Starting in the late 2010s, National Steel Car began construction of these large 6,000 cu ft capacity gondolas.  NSC 6000 CF Highside Gondola is a slightly smaller version of the popular 6400 CF series.
 
As a comparison, a legacy 52′ Mill Gondola has a capacity of 2,791 cu. Ft. These next gen gondolas also are able to carry a Gross Weight on Rail of 286,000 lbs.
 
Steel making has evolved to Electric Arc Furnaces (EAF) using steel scrap, with large integrated mills using blast furnaces on the wane. Using scrap metal in steel-making requires 60% less energy than refining from ore. Because of this shift, scrap metal and recycled materials are in high demand. With the decline of coal use, railroad coal cars have been widely used for hauling scrap metal.  The growth in the metals industry has led to new geraration of cars specifically built for scrap-hauling.
 
American Iron and Metal (AIM) is ironically a Canadian company founded in 1936 in Montreal. AIM has 90 sites worldwide, with large facilities in Montreal and Hamilton. AIM operates a fleet of 2,400 grey or black gondolas in scrap metal service using reporting marks AIMX, usually in groups of cars.
 
The Black 19000-21000 series are NSC 6000 cu.ft. (64' long), were built 2019+ and are black in color with the AIM logo.

Under Magnolia Bridge
Westbound Amtrak Empire Builder Train 7 passes under the Magnolia bridge in the Interbay neighborhood in Seattle, Washington. It is only 3.5 miles from King Street Station to complete its 2,206 miles from Chicago. The trip is scheduled to take 46 hours and 10 minutes. The Magnolia bridge is at the south end of BNSF Balmer Yard in Interbay.
 
The Empire Builder is an Amtrak long-distance passenger train that operates daily between Chicago and either Seattle or Portland via two sections west of Spokane.
 
The Magnolia Bridge was built in 1930 to connect the Seattle neighborhoods of Magnolia and Interbay over the filled-in tidelands of Smith Cove. It is one of only three road connections from Magnolia to the rest of Seattle. The bridge was damaged in the 2001 Nisqually earthquake and is currently scheduled for replacement.
 
Magnolia is the second largest neighborhood in Seattle by area, occupying a hilly peninsula northwest of downtown. Magnolia has been a part of the city since 1891. Much of the peninsula is taken up by Discovery Park, formerly the U.S. Army's Fort Lawton.

Balmer Yard 737 Fuselages
Boeing 737 fuselages in BNSF Balmer Yard waiting for transport to the Boeing plant in Renton, Washington. In 2018, BNSF delivered 10,000th fuselage to Renton by rail. In 2005, Boeing sold its Wichita division and Oklahoma operations to Spirit Aerosystems. Couple of Cupolas
Two former Burlington Northern cabooses seen in Balmer Yard in Seattle, Washington. The units are marked “Yard Service Only”. The cabooses are used as shoving platforms for the hump yard.
 
BN 12603 has a "BNSF Swoosh patch”, and was originally built for the Great Northern in 1967 as their X108.  BN 12332 is still in BN livery.
 
The cabooses were built by International Car Corp. in Kenton, Ohio. "International Car” was founded in 1924 as New City Car Co. building wooden rail cars. The plant was idle from 1939 to 1941, when it was purchased by an investor company that began to specialize in building cabooses. The plant once shipped 285 cabooses a year, 85 percent of the U. S. production.  PACCAR (Pacific Car & Foundry) purchased the company from Nationwide Industries of Chicago in 1975 for $2.5 million, a time when International Car had annual sales of $10 million. International Car Co., once the nation's leading manufacturer of railroad cabooses, announced the closing of its Kenton plant in 1983.

Boeing 737 MAX 9
In 2005, Boeing sold its Wichita division and Oklahoma operations to Spirit Aerosystems.  Today, they manufacture a significant part of the 737 fuselage, and BNSF transports them around 1,800 miles for final assembly to Washington State. At the Boeing final assembly plant in Renton, the wings, fuselage and landing gear are married together, as well as avionics and interiors are installed as it moves down the assembly line. It takes 9 days from the time an empty shell arrives at the factory until a completed plane roles out the door ready to fly to the paint shop.
 
On the bottom is a Boeing 737 Max 9 fuselage seen in BNSF’s Balmer yard in the Interbay neighborhood in Seattle, Washington. The fuselage is waiting delivered to the Boeing assembly plant in Renton.
 
Painted on the plane is a Boeing line number 8498. The Boeing line number applies to a specific airplane type and is an identifier in the production process. According to the ch-aviation database, this fuselage is an Aeromexico’s 737 MAX 9. Aeromexico currently has five Boeing 737 MAX 9, and the airline is slated to receive ten more units of this plane. Aeromexico’s Boeing 737 MAX 9 units have 181 seats. 737 illustration (top) Boeing Commercial Airplanes.

Boeing Skybox Cars
A string of specialty Boeing railcars in 2017 at BNSF Balmer Yard in Seattle, Washington. TBCX is Boeing railroad reporting mark.
 
The railroad equipment is used to transport subassemblies of Boeing’s B777 aircraft. Many railfans refer to these cars as a Skybox and variations have been in service since the mid-20th century on North American rails. These cars feature tall lids with tapered roofs on a flat car that protect the aircraft subassemblies during transport. Serving as both an alignment and assembly platforms, in transit, protective rigging fixtures secure any attached aircraft fuselage components. Once the aircraft components have reached their final destination, a gantry crane is used to remove the Skybox car cowlings and the assembly/transport jigs, with their attached parts. They are an AAR class “FW” - Flat car with hole to enable lading to be lowered due to clearance limits.

Cascadia Inn
The town of Skykomish was built by the Great Northern Railway in 1894 as a division point on the railroad. The town lies on the bank of the South Fork of the Skykomish River, and also originally had a sawmill. Settled during the building of the Great Northern, the town was dependent on the railroad. There was a GN roundhouse for “helper” engines and a substation for the electrified section eastward to Appleyard.
 
Located in the heart of the Cascade Mountains, the historic 14 room Cascadia Inn has been welcoming guests to the Skykomish Valley since 1922. 
 
Today about 20 trains a day pass through “Sky” on the BNSF Northern Transcon. Amtrak’s “Empire Builder” passes through west in the morning and east in the evening enroute between Seattle and Chicago.

BNSF Salmon Bay Bridge
This is a 2020 photo of the BNSF Salmon Bay Bridge No. 4 in the “upright and locked position”.
 
“Bridge No.4” had a calamitous failure 70 years ago that left it upright for six months. In 1914 when the Ship Canal was built and the Great Northern was building the Salmon Bay Bridge, rival railroad Northern Pacific built its own similar drawbridge across the Ship Canal just east of the Ballard Bridge.
 
In June 1948, disaster struck the Salmon Bay Bridge and the huge concrete counterweight partially separated from the superstructure of the bridge and sat right down on the tracks. During the six-month closure to repair the Salmon Bay Bridge, all Great Northern Railway traffic was diverted at Interbay to the Northern Pacific bridge. If the Salmon Bay Bridge failed today, there’s no good way around the Ship Canal, as the Northern Pacific bridge was torn down in 1976.

Ballard Lift Bridge and Locks
30 to 40 trains cross the BNSF Ballard per day, including Sounder and Amtrak passenger trains. The lift bridge provides maritime traffic to pass and access the Lake Washington Ship Canal via the locks. The Ballard Locks carry more boat traffic than any other lock in the US, and the Locks, along with the fish ladder and Botanical Gardens attract more than one million visitors annually, making it one of Seattle's top tourist attractions. The construction of the locks profoundly reshaped the topography of Seattle and the surrounding area, lowering the water level of Lake Washington and Lake Union by 8.8 feet, adding miles of new waterfront land, reversing the flow of rivers when opened in 1917. Moorage, marine services, and saltwater access made possible by the Locks support an estimated $1.2 billion in gross business sales annually, including commercial fishing companies, shipyards and marine services, vessel sales, freight and shipping services, passenger services, construction, and marinas.

Great Northern at Interbay 
The Interbay neighborhood in Seattle, Washington is in a valley between Queen Anne Hill on the east and Magnolia on the west, plus filled-in areas of Smith Cove and Salmon Bay. Much of Interbay’s land is used by BNSF Railway's Balmer Yard and BNSF Interbay Shops. In 1884 the Seattle, Lake Shore and Eastern Railway purchased all but 50 acres in Interbay and built a north–south rail line through the area. The Great Northern Railway later acquired control of the railway and constructed Interbay yard and shops. GN also developed two new coal and lumber piers, today's Piers 90 and 91, increasing industrialization of Interbay. During the 1911–1916 construction of the Lake Washington Ship Canal the Port of Seattle built Fishermen's Terminal on Salmon Bay at the north end of Interbay. Today Fisherman’s Terminal is the home port for Seattle's commercial fishing fleet. Fisherman's Terminal is home to some of the vessels in the Discovery Channel TV series Deadliest Catch.

Lake Washington Ship Canal 
Approximately eight miles long, the Lake Washington Ship Canal was created to allow passage of vessels from Puget Sound to Lake Washington. The canal's construction lowered the water level of Lake Washington by nine feet and raised the level of Salmon Bay behind the locks. Salmon Bay, previously a tidal inlet, became a freshwater body of water. The U.S. Army Corps of Engineers began on the project in 1909, and by November 1916, ships were moving through the locks. The Salmon Bay Railroad Bridge was built by the Great Northern Railway in 1913 and 1914. The lift bridge was necessary because of the construction of the Ballard Locks and the Lake Washington Ship Canal. Before the canal was built, the Great Northern tracks from Seattle went north across the east end of Salmon Bay on a curving trestle just west of the Ballard Bridge. The tracks then continued west to the shore of Puget Sound and on up to the Great Northern’s route across Stevens Pass and to Canada at Blaine.

REBUILD, NOT REPLACE
BNSF Railway initially planned to replace the Salmon Bay Bridge with a new $200 million vertical-lift bridge, but chose to repair failing components of the existing bridge following consultation with the local community. Since 1914 bridge was built, frequent maintenance and upgrades have ensured its safe and efficient use for over 100 years.

The Achilles heel of the 100 year old bridge bridge are its trunion bearings that allow the span to raise and lower. The design of the Salmon Bay Railroad Bridge is known as a “Strauss heel-trunion single-leaf bascule bridge”. BNSF replaced trunion bearings in 2013, but subsequent inspections showed further issues.

Project was awarded $25 million from the Infrastructure for Rebuilding America (INFRA) grant program. BNSF Railway will provide an additional $70 million in funding needed to complete the project. Repairs to take place during maintenance windows. Care has been taken to minimize the impacts environment. The major work will involve replacing the counterweight. Construction will last up to three years

Major Repair History:
1948 – Counterweight rebuilt
1980 – Main operating strut replaced
1995 – Main drive machinery and motors replaced
2010 – Counterweight trunnion bearings replaced
2013 – Most recent replacement of movable joints

Timber tie deck replaced multiple times over the years. Common steel maintenance such as replacing stringers and repairing corroded members has occurred throughout the life of the bridge. Operator house has been continuously updated and maintained. (BNSF illustration)

Heritage 1
BNSF started as a holding company in 1995 that purchased the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway ("Santa Fe") and Burlington Northern Railroad. The two railroads became Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF) in 1996. 
 
The first paint scheme had a thick orange stripe down the middle for the black lettering and just one yellow stripe between the orange stripe and the "dark Pullman Green" that is above and below the orange/yellow area. The Santa Fe cross logo was front heralded as Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway. The colors are based on Great Northern Railway's pre-1967 colors of Omaha Orange and Pullman Green.

GE AC4400CW
BNSF 5673 GE AC4400CW leading a northbound freight on the Scenic Sub approaching Balmer Yard next to Elliot Bay in Seattle, Washington in 2013. The photo is from the Helix Bridge. The locomotive is in the BNSF Heritage 2 paint scheme and was built in 2004.
 
The AC4400CW is a 4,400 hp locomotive built by GE Transportation Systems between 1993 and 2004. It is like the Dash 9-44CW, but features AC traction motors instead of DC, with a separate inverter per motor. Newer iterations are referred as "AC44CW". 
 
Between 1999 and 2004 BNSF purchased 121 AC4400CW locomotives (although one was wrecked). Also, forty-one AC44CWs have been placed on short-term lease to Metrolink. This leaves 79 on the BSNF roster. Over the 11 years in which it was produced, GE constructed 2,834 of the AC44CW for North American railroads.

BNSF Liveries
There are a great many variations of BNSF Paint Schemes, but the primary are the four Heritage schemes that are called H1-H4. Many locomotives retain their original paint schemes, but these units are now either being retired, or rebuilt and repainted in the Heritage III and Heritage IV schemes.
 
Heritage I (H1)
BNSF started as a holding company in 1995 that purchased the Atchison, Topeka and Santa Fe Railway ("Santa Fe") and Burlington Northern Railroad. The two railroads became Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railway (BNSF) in 1996. The first paint scheme had a thick orange stripe down the middle for the green lettering and just one yellow stripe between the orange stripe and the "dark Pullman Green" that is above and below the orange/yellow area. The Santa Fe cross logo was front heralded as Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway. The colors are based on Great Northern Railway's pre-1967 colors of Omaha Orange and Pullman Green. 
 
In 1999, the "Heritage II" (H2) scheme was introduced with ATSF-style lettering that replaced the round Santa Fe logo with the cross.
 
In 2005 the former Burlington Northern Santa Fe railroad was renamed as BNSF Railway Co. This introduced the “Heritage III” (H3) scheme with their current "swoosh" style logo. Train enthusiast nicknamed these locomotives "pumpkins" with their dominant orange color.
 
The  H4 paint scheme was introduced in 2006, is similar to H1 but with the modifications of the green replaced by black, the new logo, and a wider orange band.

BSNF ODDS & ENDS
BNSF WARBONNET (Fakebonnet)
The AT&SF Super Chief was painted in the Warbonnet paint scheme for its passenger streamliners starting in the late 1930s. In the 1990s, Santa Fe’s president Mike Haverty brought back red and silver for SuperFleet equipment. These included DASH 8-40BW, DASH 9-44CW, SD75M, GP60M & FP45s locomotives. Notable were the DASH 9-44CW 700-799 delivered from the factory as BNSF Warbonnets.
 
BNSF Executive Green & Cream
This paint scheme is featured on a small number of former BN locomotives. It’s named after Gerald Grinstein, former CEO of BNSF predecessor Burlington Northern, and is sometimes referred to informally as “Grinstein Green.” This scheme originally came out in 1993 on the BN on AC locomotives for coal service. Another nickname was the “Eddie Bauer” paint scheme because of the coloring.
 
BNSF “Yellow Bonnet”
In 1972 Santa Fe reintroduced its Warbonnet livery with a blue with yellow design named “Yellowbonnet.” This coincided with handing over of its passenger operations in 1971 to Amtrak. Santa Fe’s image was officially became blue with yellow and the Red & Silver Warbonnet largely went out of use.
 
BNSF Lease Repaint - ”Smurf”
The locomotive shown is BNSF 2042 Rebuilt EMD GP38-3 in Hodgkins, Illinois. It was built for Penn Central in 1971 and then went to the GATX Rail Locomotive Group as a lease unit. These memorable blue locomotives are the only BNSF units in this color.  Railfans have nicknamed these “Smurfs” after the blue cartoon characters. All of these are switch engines. BNSF bought them from Conrail and GATX, and rather than repainting them, they kept the blue color scheme. At this point only a couple remain in the blue scheme.

Older BNSF Locos 
Several locomotives are tied up in front of the Balmer Yard offices in 2019. Front to back: BNSF 2133 EMD GP38AC, BNSF 1551 Remote EMD SD9, and BNSF 2633 EMD GP35U. A total of 261 EMD GP38AC 4-axle road switchers were built by EMD between 1970 and 1971. It was basically a GP38 with an AR10 alternator instead of the GP38's normal generator. The SD9 is probably the rarest to still see running. A total of 471 SD9 6-axle road switcher were built by EMD between January 1954 and June 1959. The EMD GP35U is an old ATSF built in 1965 that was rebuilt into a GP35u. The rebuilt Santa Fe GP35's had 16-645E3 prime movers - presumably the original 567D3A upgraded with 645 power assemblies. The locomotives are tied up in front of the Balmer Yard offices in 2019.

Trash Train
Southbound unit trash train seen running Elliot Bay in Seattle, Washington. BNSF runs garbage trains from the Seattle and communities north. The trains go down the Seattle Sub to Vancouver, Washington, turn left and go up the Columbia River gorge to Roosevelt, Washington. The garbage goes 300 or more miles from its origin to its final resting place. Specifically designed double stack containers hold the trash. Rubberized fabric covers keep the trash in the containers. When the trains arrive in Roosevelt, the containers are put on trucks that take them up the hill to the landfill. In the summer, the odor of the loaded trains can be overwhelming.

Snohomish River Delta
The Snohomish River is the confluence of the Skykomish and the Snoqualmie Rivers.  As the Snohomish approaches Puget Sound, it turns north and divides the land to the east and the Port Gardner Peninsula where most of Everett lies. The entire river system drains about 1,980 square miles which flow out of the Cascade Mountains to the east. After reaching the top of the peninsula, the river turns west to empty into Port Gardner Bay.
 
The three major sloughs that branch off from the river wind through a marshy area called the Snohomish River Estuary. This is the second largest river basin on Puget Sound, after the Skagit. 
 
Smith Island lies between the Snohomish River and Union Slough.
 
Spencer Island is between Union Slough and Steamboat Slough.
 
North Ebey Island is between Steamboat Slough and Ebey Slough.
 
From South to North BNSF has to traverse this large river delta.
BNSF Railway Snohomish River Turnbridge
BNSF - Union Slough Bridge (fixed)
BNSF - Steamboat Slough Turnbridge
BNSF - Ebey Slough Turnbridge

Historic Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railway (BNSF) swing bridge over the Snohomish River in Everett, Washington. The bridge is a Warren through truss and was built in 1922 for the Great Northern Railway (GN).

The Snohomish River is the confluence of the Skykomish and the Snoqualmie Rivers.  As the Snohomish approaches Puget Sound, it turns north and divides the land to the east and the Port Gardner Peninsula where most of Everett lies. The entire river system drains about 1,980 square miles which flow out of the Cascade Mountains to the east. After reaching the top of the peninsula, the river turns west to empty into Port Gardner Bay.
 
The three major sloughs that branch off from the river wind through a marshy area called the Snohomish River Estuary. This is the second largest river basin on Puget Sound, after the Skagit.

Modern Frog
Notice the warning sign by the switch? This indicates the presence of a “Lift Frog” switch. In a switch with a “flange bearing frog” the flange of the wheel supports the weight of the railcar of locomotive. BNSF has been a leader in the use of Lift Frog switches, and had installed over 100 by 2010. Today, they are becoming very common on the BNSF system. The purpose of Lift Frogs is to eliminate the 'gaps' of frogs on the higher speed/tonnage side of the switch. There are no speed restrictions on the high speed side, but the low speed side thought the Lift Frog is limited to 10 mph.
 
Southbound Empty BNSF coal train passes through Delta Junction in Everett, Washington as it is strung across the Snohomish River Swing Bridge. The train is departing the BNSF Bellingham Sub and entering the Rogers Main (NP) along the edge of Delta Yard.

Lift Frog
A sign warning “Caution Hy-Rail Vehicles: Lift Frog” accompany the specialty switches.
 
Hy-Rail trucks are dual-mode vehicles that operate on both railroad tracks and roads (highway + railway = hi-rail). In addition to their rubber tires, hi-rail trucks also have a set of flanged steel wheels that, when deployed, allow the vehicle to travel on railways. Care has to be taken when they cross a lift frog switch.
 
In a switch with a “flange bearing frog” the flange of the wheel supports the weight of the railcar of locomotive. Lift frogs are used in turnouts where the through (straight) route is heavily used, and the diverging (curved) route is only used on occasion and at low speed. The frog is tread-bearing, with a normal rail surface, on the through route, and is flange-bearing on the diverging route.
 
The wheel on the diverging rail is lifted over the through rail in the frog, hence the name. The though route does not need a guardrail, but a special guardrail is used on the diverging route to keep railcar from derailing. Lift Frogs are used on set-out tracks or lightly-used industry tracks that diverge from high-speed, high-tonnage mainlines.

Rogers Main
Southbound Empty BNSF coal train after through Delta Junction in Everett, Washington as it is strung across the Snohomish River Swing Bridge. The train is departing the BNSF Bellingham Sub and entering the Rogers Main (NP) along the edge of Delta Yard.  After the train reaches PA Junction, the train will head to Lowell, WA on the BNSF Scenic Sub and summit the Cascades at Stevens Pass on the BNSF Northern Transcon. BNSF 6416 GE ES44AC is on point with BNSF 8465 EMD SD70ACe and BNSF 4656 GE C44-9W trailing.
 
The Rogers Main runs between Delta Junction and PA Junction in Everett on former Northern Pacific Roadbed. In 2015, BNSF completed a large project around the Everett area to expand Delta and Bayside Yards. The WSDOT High-Speed Rail Corridor project, realigned the Rogers Main to connect with the Bayside Line, to reduce conflict with through trains waiting for commuter windows and a slot through the Everett tunnel.

A Longtime Industry for Everett
In the 1890’s the first mill established a Weyerhaeuser presence in Everett that lasted for decades:
 
• Mill A (1903-1980) was a showcase, experimental mill on Port Gardner Bay;
• Mill B (1915-1979) was the first electric mill in the U.S. and supplier to East Coast markets, located on the Snohomish River at the northern tip of Everett;
• Mill C (1923-1977) was a hemlock plant lying east of Mill B; the Kraft Pulp Mill (1953-1992) and Mill E (1971-1985) were on the Snohomish River, east of Mill B.
• Kraft Mill: Weyerhaeuser used this for paper production.
• Mill “E”: Weyerhaeuser operated a wood treatment facility on this property.
 
An elegant office building that was built at Mill A to showcase its products in 1923 currently [2021] is owned by the Port of Everett and is located at the Port's Boxcar Park. Following the closure of its last mill, Weyerhaeuser stayed in Everett years longer doing environmental cleanup at its plant sites.

Weyerhaeuser Mill B
Starting in 1915, Weyerhaeuser Company built the 100-acre sawmill complex called Mill “B”. This was one of many mills along the Snohomish River in north Everett. The different mills had different specialties. The facility was the first all-electrically-powered lumber mill in the United States. Weyerhaeuser's Mill B was a key lumber processing facility producing lumber shipped to the East Coast by ship and rail. The Weyerhaeuser Company Mill B in Everett could turn out four hundred thousand feet of lumber in eight hours. The plant’s huge capacity revolutionized the US timber industry. Weyerhaeuser continued to grow during the 1910s, by the end of the decade operating 22 processing plants across the US. Photo - Weyerhaeuser Archives

Life After Weyerhaeuser
The Port of Everett purchased the 85-acre Riverside Business Park from Weyerhaeuser in 1998. Weyerhaeuser operated a Mill on the site from 1915-1980s. The environmental cleanup on the site concluded in 1999. Over the years, the Port has improved the property with fill, roadways, utilities and raised the property out of the flood plain. The property has 38 usable acres that have been sub-divided into nine parcels. 
 
In 2018 a 102,500-square-foot building for an aerospace supplier and a distribution center for Federal Express were built.  Motor Trucks was first in the park with an International truck dealership in 2010. 
 
The county owns another parcel in the business park and leases it to Republic Services to transfer waste onto railroad cars to ship away to landfills.

Regional Disposal Company (RDC)
The former Weyerhaeuser Mill B site is home to the regional site leased by Republic Services that transfers trash from the area onto railroad cars. The trains transport trash over 300 miles to the landfills in the arid side of the Columbia River Gorge.
 
Garbage from Whatcomb County is loaded at a facility between Bellingham and Ferndale.
 
Garbage Skagit County is loaded at Whitney. This is a location on the Anacortes Branch.
 
Snohomish County garbage is loaded at Everett, Washington.
 
The garbage loads funnel into BNSF Delta Yard at Everett, Washington. Here they are made into 6,000 foot long trains for movement to the Roosevelt Regional Landfill at Roosevelt, Washington in the Columbia River Gorge.
 
The loaded garbage train from Everett is BNSF symbolled as EVEROO. The empty returning train is the ROOEVE.
 
BNSF Railway and Union Pacific garbage trains have been running for more than 30 years from the Seattle area. Both railroads move container trains loaded with waste south on BNSF’s Seattle Subdivision (UP has trackage rights on this line) before heading east through the Gorge on their own lines — BNSF on the north side and UP on the south side. Each railroad has contracts with different companies to move garbage, resulting in six or more trains per day (2 are UP and 4 are BNSF) along the main lines of the Pacific Northwest.

Trains Transport Trash Over 300 Miles 
Pacific Northwest trash is transported by rail to two landfill locations in the Columbia River Gorge in Washington and Oregon. For over 30 years Union Pacific and BNSF hauled trash from Seattle to the landfills. Six trains a day or more use the BNSF Seattle Subdivision (Union Pacific has trackage rights) to move the trash.
 
The Cascade Range receives over 100 inches of rain on the west side. East of the mountains along the Columbia River Gorge are the “dry side” receives little rainfall, where the regional landfills are located. The arid region is ideal for a landfill because the geology helps prevent runoff from entering aquifer.
 
The BNSF trash trains assemble trains from nine different Pacific Northwest transfer stations and haul it to the Roosevelt Regional Landfill operated by Republic Services, 140 miles east of Vancouver, WA. On average the containers weigh around 48 tons, with 300 double -stack containers per train. The two daily trash trains originate in BNSF yards in Everett and Seattle.
 
Seattle also sends trash to the Columbia Ridge landfill on Union Pacific Railroad. Washington Waste Systems transports and dispose waste for the city of Seattle. Up to 140 containers are loaded onto double-stack well car in Seattle UP Argo Yard for transport to the landfill. On alternate days three times a week, Union Pacific transports seventy-car trains Columbia Ridge on BNSF tracks, then at Portland uses the UP mainline to the Columbia Ridge landfill. One day a week a UP train runs from Blakeslee Junction, WA to the landfill.

Union Pacific Argo Yard
A view or Union Pacific Argo Yard looking towards the seaport. Argo also includes subyards Manar and Van Asselt. Argo is the UP intermodal terminal (domestic and international) in Seattle as well as a truck to rail transfer station for solid waste. Argo yard is almost exclusively used for intermodal traffic and interchanges between BNSF and UP. Van Asselt and Manar yards are used for carload freight originating and terminating at industries on UP in Seattle and Tukwila. 
 
BNSF’s 177-mile Seattle Subdivision, connecting Seattle with Portland, Oregon, is the most heavily trafficked rail line in Washington State. This line provides access to and from the major Pacific Coast ports BNSF and UP trains (via BNSF trackage rights). 
 
Seattle sends trash to the Columbia Ridge landfill in Oregon from Union Pacific Argo Yard. Waste Management Inc. subsidiary Washington Waste Systems transports and dispose waste for the city of Seattle. Up to 140 containers are loaded onto double-stack well car in Seattle UP Argo Yard for transport to the landfill.  On alternate days three times a week, Union Pacific transports seventy-car trains Columbia Ridge on BNSF tracks, then at Portland uses the UP mainline to the Columbia Ridge landfill. One day a week a UP train runs from Blakeslee Junction, WA to the landfill.

BNSF Interbay Yard Trash Train
Trash train H-INBROO (Seattle Interbay Yard – Roosevelt) seen in BSNF Interbay Yard in Seattle. In addition to Delta Yard in Everett, Interbay serves as the origination point of the second daily trash train from Seattle to Republic Services regional landfill at Roosevelt, Washington, about 140 miles east of Vancouver, Wash.
 
BNSF collects trash at nine different regional collection points around the Northwest that can include trash from Canada and Alaska. Each train averages about 300 double-stacked trash containers with each container weighing an average of 48 tons completely loaded.
 
Republic Services covers municipal garbage service for nearly three-quarters of all households in Washington state. Sixty percent of the trash is derived from municipal solid waste with the remaining 40 percent split evenly between debris from construction/demolition and contaminated soils, known as “dirty dirt”.
 
Upon arrival at Roosevelt, the containers are taken out of the well cars and trucked the final few miles up to the landfill. After trash trains have been unloaded at Roosevelt, the empties head back west through the gorge and back north toward Seattle.

BSNF Fallbridge Sub
One of the two daily trash trains from the Seattle and Everett arrives in Wishram, Washington in the Columbia River Gorge. The Celilo Bridge is visible to the left of the train, as it passes through the junction. Columbia River Gorge
This is a view looking east in the Columbia River Gorge, showing Wishram in context of the rugged landscape. The BNSF Fallbridge Subdivision runs on the north bank of the Columbia River, a 230 mile long route starting at Pasco to Vancouver, then south to Portland, region. The sub is considered part of the BNSF Northern Transcon to Chicago. The bridge at Wishram leads to the BNSF Oregon Trunk Subdivision that stretches 220 miles between Wishram and Chemult, Oregon. The BNSF Wishram Yard in on the left (north) side of the river.
 
On the south side of the Columbia River is the first railroad built, the Oregon Railroad and Navigation Company. The OR&N had 1,143 miles of track running east from Portland to NE Oregon, NE Washington, and northern Idaho. OR&N started as an independent railroad in 1896, but Union Pacific purchased a majority stake in the line in 1898. Today, this is a busy mainline route for Union Pacific.
 
The Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway was built by James J. Hill who had built the Great Northern Railway. Hill also who controlled the Northern Pacific and Chicago, Burlington and Quincy railroads. GN, NP, and CB&Q lines served to link Chicago with Seattle. Oregon Railway and Navigation Company on the south side of the Columbia River connected GN and NP trains to Portland.
 
Edward Harriman, who owned UP and SP railroads, took control of the OR&N and denied Hill’s railroads access to the route along the Columbia River. This forced Hill decided to build a new line from Spokane to Portland along the north bank of the river. The new line would be half owned by the Great Northern and half by the Northern Pacific.

The Northwest's Own Railway
The Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway was built as a direct link into Portland, Oregon for the Northern Pacific and Great Northern. The SP&S survived as a bridge road for over 60 years until on March 2, 1970 it merged into the Burlington Northern system.
 
In the late 1960s Wishram was a crew change where the Oregon trunk secondary crossed the Columbia River south into Oregon. The SP&S Wishram yard that blocked trains heading westward for Portland.  To the east were connections with Great Northern and Northern Pacific in Spokane. Wishram served as a division point with engine house for repairs and service, and a car shop. Wishram is about 106 miles east of Portland and 114 miles west of Pasco.
 
The Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway was built by James J. Hill who had built the Great Northern Railway. Hill also who controlled the Northern Pacific and Chicago, Burlington and Quincy railroads. GN, NP, and CB&Q lines served to link Chicago with Seattle. Oregon Railway and Navigation Company on the south side of the Columbia River connected GN and NP trains to Portland.
 
Today the former SP&S is the BNSF Fallbridge Subdivision, which runs on the north bank of the Columbia River. This is a  230 mile long route starting at Pasco to Vancouver, then south to Portland, and is considered part of the BNSF Northern Transcon to Chicago. By the 1980s, the repair shop and engine house were demolished as today Wishram is a minor yard.

Spanning the Mighty Columbia
The Oregon Trunk Rail Bridge or Celilo Bridge was constructed in 1912 over the Columbia River between Washington State and Oregon. There are eight steel truss spans and several deck girder spans, and in 1957 a vertical-lift section as added. Mount Hood can been in the upper right of the photo. BNSF Wishram Yard is in the foreground.
 
The bridge is downstream of the site of Celilo Falls, now submerged by water from The Dalles Dam. Originally, the Celilo Canal passed beneath a swing span on the southern side of the bridge. In 1957 with the completion of The Dalles Dam inundated the Celilo canal. Starting in October 1956, the entire bridge had to be raised by up to 5 feet over its entire length. A vertical-lift-type span was installed on the first span north of the swing span for river navigation. The legacy swing span south of the lift span is now locked in place.
 
On the north end of the bridge where the rail line from Bend meets the BNSF Portland to Pasco mainline there is a Wye. The south end of the bridge crosses over and has an interchange with the Union Pacific mainline. The bridge is 2,396 feet long excluding the two Wye branches at the north end.
 
The bridge connected the Oregon Trunk Railway Company extended southward from Wishram to Bend, Oregon. Today, this line is BNSF Railway’s Oregon Trunk Subdivision that stretches 220 miles. The line passes through the pine forests of Central Oregon, passes through an ancient lava flow near Bend, cross high bridges and winds through the scenic Deschutes River Canyon.

Oregon Trunk Rail Bridge 1912
View of the Oregon Trunk Rail Bridge across the Columbia River near Wishram Washington. The photograph is taken from the tracks on the Washington side of the bridge looking south through the trusses. The bridge is also known as the Celilo Bridge.
 
The Oregon Trunk Railway Bridge, constructed in 1911, was the first structure to cross this spectacular gorge. Prior to construction the only crossing of the Crooked River in this region was located about a mile upstream, where the canyon's sheer basalt walls begin tapering gradually into the surrounding landscape.
 
In the early 1900's, railroad tycoons James J. Hill of the Spokane, Portland & Seattle Railway (SP&S) and Edward Harriman of the Union Pacific began a fierce battle to open central Oregon rail traffic. This battle, one of the greatest in railroad history, played out in the courts, where the SP&S triumphed. The Oregon Trunk Railway, a subsidiary of the SP&S, ran from Celilo Falls on the Columbia to Bend - James Hill was on hand in Bend on October 5, 1911 to drive a "Golden Spike" celebrating the line's official opening.

Wishram - Heart of SP&S
A view from the Amtrak platform in Wishram, Washington.

The Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway was built as a direct link into Portland, Oregon for the Northern Pacific and Great Northern. The SP&S survived as a bridge road for over 60 years until on March 2, 1970 it merged into the Burlington Northern system.
 
In the late 1960s Wishram was a crew change where the Oregon trunk secondary crossed the Columbia River south into Oregon. The SP&S Wishram yard that blocked trains heading westward for Portland.  To the east were connections with Great Northern and Northern Pacific in Spokane. Wishram served as a division point with engine house for repairs and service, and a car shop. Whishram is about 106 miles east of Portland and 114 miles west of Pasco.
 
The Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway was built by James J. Hill who had built the Great Northern Railway. Hill also who controlled the Northern Pacific and Chicago, Burlington and Quincy railroads. GN, NP, and CB&Q lines served to link Chicago with Seattle.

Today the former SP&S is the BNSF Fallbridge Subdivision, which runs on the north bank of the Columbia River. This is a  230 mile long route starting at Pasco to Vancouver, then south to Portland, and is considered part of the BNSF Northern Transcon to Chicago. By the 1980s, the repair shop and engine house were demolished as today Wishram is a minor yard.

BNSF Firefighting Train
Drought conditions and high winds are common in the Columbia River Gorge, so BNSF plans for fighting wildfires on or near their tracks. Tank cars full of water to combat wildfires are staged in areas prone to fire conditions like Wishram and Pasco. BNSF in the Pacific Northwest has unique firefighting assets with specially equipped trains that to extinguish fires.
 
The Pasco train has two tank cars, a “fire” car and a command center caboose. The tank cars contain thousands of gallons of water, and the fire car is equipped with aqueous firefighting foam. An onboard generator in the caboose provides power for the cars and can also be used to power work lights, radios and other emergency equipment.
 
The Wishram train houses its generators, pipes and pump systems under three tank cars. It also has a caboose that is equipped with a spray bar and water cannon, and acts as the command center when called into service. This train was built to protect the south-central portion of the state.
 
The train works closely with the local fire departments so firefighters that get on the train, with BNSF train crews moving the train to the fires. The caboose acts as a transport for the firefighters, then once at the site, they use hoses and the cannon to shoot water -- able to reach flames up to 30 feet away. The train can get  firefighters to places firetrucks can’t access and where there are no water sources. A firetruck carries an average of 500 gallons of water, while the train’s tanks carry 30,000 gallons.

REAL “FOAMERS”
BNSF Firefighting Foam Fire Car seen in Whishram, Washington as an adjunct to the fire train.
 
Water has historically been the fire service’s cooling agent of choice, but adding Class A foam can enhance the firefighting effectiveness. Class A foams were developed in the mid-1980s for fighting wildfires. Class A foams lower the surface tension of the water, which assists in the wetting and saturation of Class A fuels with water. It penetrates and extinguishes embers at depth. This aids fire suppression and can prevent reignition.

Loads and Empties
An empty trash train pulls into Whishram, Washington just a loaded trash train pulls into the yard. It is a daily logistical battle to get the two loaded trash trains to the intermodal unloading site by the landfill and the empties back 300 miles to Seattle.

Running Up That Hill

BNSF collects trash at nine different regional collection points around the Northwest that can include trash from Canada and Alaska. Each train averages about 300 double-stacked trash containers with each container weighing an average of 48 tons completely loaded.
 
Republic Services covers municipal garbage service for nearly three-quarters of all households in Washington state. Sixty percent of the trash is derived from municipal solid waste with the remaining 40 percent split evenly between debris from construction/demolition and contaminated soils, known as “dirty dirt”.

Trash train H-INBROO (Seattle Interbay Yard – Roosevelt) seen in BSNF Interbay Yard in Seattle. In addition to Delta Yard in Everett, Interbay serves as the origination point of the second daily trash train from Seattle to Republic Services regional landfill at Roosevelt, Washington, about 140 miles east of Vancouver.

BNSF Fallbridge Sub
A view from Mayer State Park in The Dalles, Oregon looking north across the Columbia River at Rowena Gap. An eastbound BNSF local seen near Lyle, Washington. On the right a westbound BNSF freight is approaching.

The trains are dwarfed by the walls off the gorge, which is over 2,500 feet to the top.

The BNSF Fallbridge Subdivision runs on the north bank of the Columbia River, a 230 mile long route starting at Pasco to Vancouver, then south to Portland, region.

Washington side of the Columbia River, viewed from Mayer State Park in Oregon. Rowena Crest is 700 feet above the Columbia River at the upstream end of Rowena Plateau. This is a miles-long point of high land that juts out into the Columbia River. The river flows around this promontory through a relatively narrow section of the Gorge known as the Rowena Gap. This a 5.5 miles long by one-mile wide water gap was cut in the Ice Age Floods. The Oregon side of the Ortley Anticline is known as the "Rowena Basalts". Six separate basalt flows can be counted in the 1,000-foot-high cliffs of the Rowena Gap.

This narrow part of the gorge funnels the wind, that can be quite intense at times. This area is popular with wind surfers.

Parking Brakes
Ever wonder why there is a chain on some locomotive trucks? This is for the “parking brake”. All locomotives have standard manual mechanical hand brakes. Some newer units have Locomotive Parking Brakes using automated electric motor driven systems that also incorporate the standard manual interfaces found on mechanical hand brakes. These are not that common at this point. When a locomotive is parked, the engineer sets the brakes. On a train with DPU units, commonly just the lead locomotives have parking brakes set.

“Securement”
A conductor from the crew taking over the unattended, parked train walks the train to release the freight car handbrakes using a brake stick. Some conductors use brake sticks to assist applying or releasing hand brakes. Brake sticks are also ideal for opening knuckles, or operating angle cocks.
 
For added safety all train cars are equipped with manual braking systems. Railroad safety regulations require that handbrakes be applied to a number of individual cars to keep the train in place, with or without the air brakes. The number of brakes set is determined by a chart that uses the total tonnage of the train and the grade of the track to determine how many cars have handbrakes set. This takes a while at about 3 minutes per car, and usually 8-10 cars (or more) to manually set (or release) the freight car brakes.
 
The Lac-Mégantic rail disaster in Quebec ten years ago with a runaway parked train caused new focus on securing a parked freight train. Securement procedure involve several elements to assure that a parked train will not move.
 
If it’s just a crew change hand-off, the crew sets the air brake, since the train is not left unsupervised. When a crew leaves the train unmanned, a full securement procedure is required. A checklist is filled out that notifies the relieving crew of what was done for the securement.
 
Ever wonder why trains are left unattended and still running? This allows the lead engine to keep the air brakes pressurized, keeping the train in place.
 
The locomotive cabs are locked. There are a number of safety measures to assure no trespassers can tamper with the train.

DESERTS + MOUNTAINS
The Union Pacific line through Las Vegas was originally built by Union Pacific predecessor, the Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railway. This line presents some of the most extreme railroad operating conditions in North America.

Today, this line is part of the Union Pacific Rocky Mountain Division in the UP Northern Region. It is now considered two subdivisions:

The Cima Sub - Total route miles: 172.3
West end: Yermo, CA - MP 162.0
East end: Las Vegas, NV - MP 334.3

The Caliente Sub - Total route miles: 242.4 
West end: Las Vegas, NV - MP 334.3
East end: Milford, UT - MP 576.7

The ore train show in the previous posts will travel from Las Vegas to LA over the Cima Sub, on the western portion of the San Pedro, Los Angeles and Salt Lake Railroad, the Cima. The line ranges in elevation from over 11,000 feet in the Spring Mountains, to 282 feet below sea level in Death Valley. Following the Mojave River, the rails pass through the Afton Canyon then cross the dunes to Kelso. This is also where a 2.2% climb over Cima Hill about 400 miles west of Las Vegas.

On March 27, 2023, one of these ore trains got into serious trouble and derailed 3 miles west of Kelso. Reports are the 154 car ore train had broken apart on the steep 2.2% Cima Hill grad grade, and the two lead locomotives and 55 hoppers cars ran away down the grade. The crew managed to get off and there were no injuries. The last GPS report on the lead engine showed the train moving at 118 mph. The downgrade speed is limited to 15mph, so this ended in a spectacular wreck. The line was closed 26 hours until repairs could be made.

Utah Iron Ore to Los Angeles
The SA Recycling terminal in the Port of Long Beach has topped a total of 2.5 million tons in exports of iron ore since October 2020. Iron ore was a significant pivot for SA Recycling, since their roots are in shipping scrap metal to asia. SA Recycling has more than 75 facilities located across eight states in the U.S., with more than 30 facilities located in California. The market had shifted so pricing and availability were tight, so they entered the iron ore export market.
 
Starting in 2013, they has received iron ore mined in the western United States via railroad. The material is loaded onto bulk cargo ships that sail to ports in East Asia. This provided an opportunity for both SA Recycling and the Port.
 
There have been challenges with the ore supply. The only current operating iron mine in the US outside the Lake Superior area was the Iron Mountain mine, formerly called the Comstock-Mountain Lion mine, west of Cedar City, in Iron County, Utah.
 
The mine shut down in October 2014 due to falling ore prices. Operated by CML Metals, Inc. the mine produced ore with 54% iron. The ore was treated onsite, producing a concentrate containing 65% iron. The concentrate was transported by rail to California, then shipped to China. In the beginning CML Metals operated three 92-car trains every week, from Iron Springs to the Port of Long Beach.
 
In 2015 the assets of CML Metals were sold to a new company called Black Iron LLC. In 2017 Black Iron LLC declared Chapter 11 bankruptcy. Black Iron LLC was reorganized as Utah Iron LLC in 2020 and iron ore shipments via Union Pacific Railroad resumed.

CSX Radnor Yard - Cars are being “cut” so they can roll down the hump and be directed by computer and sorted by destination in the classification yard. A radio tag on each car identifies it to the computer, which knows the cars destination, and weight. CSX Nashville Hump Yard
Nashville is a key hub in the CSX system, routing sixty trains per day through the Nashville Area toward five key cities: Atlanta, Birmingham, Chicago, Louisville, and Memphis. Forty of these trains simply pass through; the rest are “hubbed” in a classification yard.
 
Radnor Yard, four miles south of downtown Nashville on the east side of the L&N main line south, was opened by the L&N in 1954, and can hold 7,905 cars. There are 13 receiving tracks and a 56-track classification yard, classifying 1,700 to 2,100 cars per day in 1998. The site covers 517 acres. 
 
CSX closed the hump-portion of its in 2017 as part of an operational shift led by then-CEO Hunter Harrison. Eight of CSX’s 12 hump yards were converted to flat-switching facilities before his death in December. CSX struggled to adapt its Nashville operations to Harrison's flat-switching model. In 2018 the Radnor Yard hump was re-opened as flat-switching could not effectively handle the volume of traffic through the yard. Classification (hump) yards are a backbone of railroad operations. Individual carload traffic accounts for 60% to 70% of total rail traffic (excluding intermodal).
 
Hump yards are massive facilities where trains are broken down and cars are sorted by pushing them over a hill. Gravity sending them down different to tracks by destination. Flat-switch yards move train cars using locomotive power, not gravity.
 
The yard uses Trainyard Tech, LLC CLASSMASTER™ hump yard process control system at CSX’s 56-classification-track Radnor Yard. The companies’ software is the first to apply standard industrial automation technology to the railway industry.

Hump Yard “Pin Puller”
CSX Radnor Yard “Pin Puller” who is not only “cutting” cars so they can roll down the hump, but also is an RCO operator (remote control) that is controlling the engine pushing the cars up the hump. A Pin Puller Scoreboard Display is at the end of the hump walkway that directs the Pin Puller on where to uncouple the cars.
 
Assuming no hazardous material issues, the pin puller at the hump crest will probably allow only one (and in some cases two) loads to uncouple at a time.  Multiple empties coupled together and destined for the same classification track would be allowed to remain coupled together as they roll down the hill and through the retarders.  The number of "multiple empties coupled together," depends on how the hump was designed and what the retarder technology is capable of handling.  The maximum number is somewhere between three and five empty cars.
 
Cars are being “cut” so they can roll down the hump and be directed by computer and sorted by destination in the classification yard. A radio tag on each car identifies it to the computer, which knows the cars destination, and weight. The system even tracks wind speed, and applies braking by squeezing the wheels in a “retarder” that regulates the car speed. This creates the sweeping sound. The cars can’t exceed 4 mph to prevent damage when the cars roll into the line of other freight cars on the classification tracks. It works sort of like a post office sorting mail. Each classification track represents a destination. After the cars are sorted, they become outbound trains and continue on their journey.

Where every day is Hump Day!
Hump yards are massive facilities where trains are broken down and cars are sorted by pushing them over a hill. Gravity sending them down different to tracks by destination. Flat-switch yards move train cars using locomotive power, not gravity.
 
Radnor Yard, four miles south of downtown Nashville on the east side of the L&N main line south, was opened by the L&N in 1954, and can hold 7,905 cars. There are 13 receiving tracks and a 56-track classification yard, classifying 1,700 to 2,100 cars per day in 1998. The site covers 517 acres. 
 
Nashville is a key hub in the CSX system, routing sixty trains per day through the Nashville Area toward five key cities: Atlanta, Birmingham, Chicago, Louisville, and Memphis. Forty of these trains simply pass through; the rest are “hubbed” in a classification yard.

Welded Rail Plant
The Nashville Rail Welding Plant is located in the CSX's Radnor Yard complex in Nashville, Tennessee. The facility is currently mothballed.

This plant produced continuous welded rails (CWR) by the Electric Flash Pressure Butt Weld process. The plant is laid out in a north and south configuration, with the welding machines being enclosed in a building at the south end. There are two independently operated welding stations in the building designated as the east and west welders, each providing a separate string of CWR. 

Immediately north of the building are hydraulic machines, into which the CWR strings are inserted. These machines, through pressure contact with the rail and a hydraulic drive, provide the power to push the CWR onto the rail cars designed to transport the rail to the field for installation. Between the power source and the rail cars (approximately 200 feet) are a series of moveable guides and rollers to position the rails in their proper place on the rail train.

There are two loading tracks to hold the rail trains while receiving the CWR. This rail train consists of 27 flat cars, 24 of which are spacer and support cars, with an upright about 10 feet from each end to support the rails, in four tiers of ten welded rails each. The two end cars are equipped with moveable bulkheads to support the rail ends in their proper position tie down car is placed in the middle of the train equipped similar to the support and spacer cars. A tie down car is placed in the middle of the train equipped similar to the support and spacer cars. It additionally has an "A" frame arrangement across the car at the center so the CWR strings may be clamped to the car, preventing movement of the rail lengthwise.

Welded Rail Train
CSX 483 GE AC44CW on point of a northbound welded rail train in Chattanooga, Tennessee. This is the CSX line from Atlanta to Nashville, and at this point it skirts along the edge of the Norfolk Southern DeButts classification yard. The waterways and mountain ridges in this part of the country dictate the location of the tracks.
 
Modern railroads use continuous welded rail (CWR) a lot instead of the traditional jointed rail. Specialized factories take traditional 39′ rails and weld them end to end to form the quarter mile lengths. CWR is preferred because it has has no joints to sag or fail, and limit wheel and track wear. The rails are then transported to where they will be installed by rail trains, and dropped beside the tracks for later installation.
 
Specialized flat cars hold 13 rails per tier and as many as three tiers can be transported at a time. The rail is loaded onto the cars as it is welded on rollers. The lengths of the rails welded determine the number of cars needed. Usually 41-ft. flat cars are used, requiring one car for every 39-ft. rail welded.
 
Rail trains have speed restrictions of 30 m.p.h. and are usually operated by experienced crews, as they require more expertise.

Rail sections stockpiled for the BNSF Welded Rail plant in Laurel, Montana.

BNSF Welded Rail Plant
Continuous welded rail (CWR) also known as ribbon rail, has fewer seams that that require less maintenance and allow trains to travel at higher speeds. Before the invention of CWR, rail was jointed, meaning bolted together that lead to  much more maintenance. Jointed rail is primarily used today within rail yards, where trains are required to move slowly. 
 
To turn the steel sticks into CWR, the complexes operate in assembly-line fashion to weld the pieces together using a fusion welding process.
 
Rail is manufactured by steel rail producers that send the sections to us as 80-foot “sticks.” These arrive by train on flat cars at the three BNSF rail complexes: Laurel, Montana; Pueblo, Colorado; and Springfield, Missouri. Here they are offloaded and stored to be turned into sections up to 1,680-foot-long (nearly one-third of a mile) of continuous welded rail (CWR).
 
Cranes move the rail sections to the plant where is it welded together. The completed nearly one-third of a mile long CWR segments load directly form the plant into specialized rai trains for transport.

CP Shoreham Terminal
Located in northeast Minneapolis, CP's Shoreham intermodal terminal provides easy access to Wisconsin, Iowa, South Dakota, North Dakota and Minnesota. The 230-acre former SOO Line Shoreham Yards has been in service since 1880s. The former SOO Line Shops were demolished in 2019 to make way for expanded Intermodal operations.

Seen are CP 2204 and CP 2207, both Rebuilt EMD GP20C-ECO (DRS-20). GP20C-ECOs use just enough rebuilt components to designate them a rebuild. The GP20C-ECOs feature a new frame, fuel tank, long hood, and cab with CP providing trucks, prime mover, and alternator (along with many other smaller components), mainly from retired CP GP9s, that are rebuilt and reused in the locomotives. The units resemble a GP60's long hood and feature a snoot nose, which set the cab back slightly on the frame to make room for the additional length.

La Crosse - Grand Crossing
Canadian Pacific's former Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad mainline crosses BNSF's former Chicago, Burlington and Quincy mainline on four railroad diamonds where the two double tracks cross.
 
With the advent of the Bakken oil boom, BNSF built 4 miles of double track through La Crosse in 2015. BNSF carries crude oil from the Bakken fields in North Dakota and Montana, bound for refineries to the east and south. This greatly increased rail traffic through La Crosse.
 
Just north of the crossing is BNSF’s North La Crosse Yard and crew change point. The 262 mile BNSF Aurora Subdivision runs St. Croix Subdivision in La Crosse, Wisconsin, to the Chicago Subdivision in Aurora, Illinois. It is part of the Chicago, Illinois, to Seattle, Washington, BNSF Northern Transcon. The original line created by the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad ran out of Aurora, Illinois to Oregon, Illinois. In 1885, the line was continued from Oregon to connect to St. Paul, Minnesota.
 
The Canadian Pacific Tomah Subdivision runs 103 miles from La Crosse, WI in the west to Portage, WI in the east. The line crosses the Mississippi River between La Crescent, MN and La Crosse. Junctions in La Crescent lead to the River Subdivision to the north and the Marquette Subdivision to the south. East of Portage, the rails continue as the Watertown Subdivision. Interstate 90 runs roughly parallel to the rail line. The Tomah Subdivision was previously the Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad (Milwaukee Road). The Soo Line took it over in 1986 before Canadian Pacific did so in the 1990s.
