Grand Crossing Maintenance
Mainline railroad diamonds require constant inspection and maintenance. As the wheels cross the gap in the diamond, they exert tremendous force, and this eventually causes wear and or damage to the points of the frog. Canadian Pacific's former Chicago, Milwaukee, St. Paul and Pacific Railroad mainline crosses BNSF's former Chicago, Burlington and Quincy mainline in La Crosse, Wisconsin. A welder is seen repairing the diamond at the Grand Crossing. Frequency of repair and welders repairing the crossing frogs is largely a function of size, age, speed and tonnage over the crossing.

There is not a material that can be commercially made that can take the impact abuse of 110-135 ton cars constantly beating on it for very long as wheels cross the flangeways and jump the 2 1/2" x 1 7/8" gap. The sharper the crossing angle, the worse wear gets. It is very common for explosive hardened manganese castings to fail at the point or corner of the side of a casting. Chunks up to 8"long to 2" deep break off and you have to lay welding bead back in the hole to beef up the failed casting to match the original profile. You have to lay the bead back in the hole with no gaps or holidays - otherwise you have instant failure. The welder has to also be careful about overheating the material he is adding bead to for fear of making it weaker.

Manganese steel castings used in railroad diamonds is the toughest steel known. The workhardening and abrasion resistant properties of manganese steel provide long life under the severest service conditions. Explosion hardening enhances the casting so the lifetime of the high manganese steel crossing can be increased by 35%.

Railroad Tie Life Cycle
The CPC LaCrosse Yard had centerbeam cars with newly treated railroad cross ties, old coal gondolas with scrapped ties from a tie replacement project, and gondolas with fresh cut railroad ties heading to a tie plant for treatment.
 
Although technological advances have led to crossties to made from concrete, steel, and plastic composites, wood ties still account for over 93% of railroad track applications.  Wood ties have been used since the mid-1800s, and after being treated with a wood preservative, they can last 30 years or more. Crossties support the vertical and lateral loads transmitted to the tie through the rails. Plus wood is a renewable resource.
 
Just before the 1900s, tie manufacturers started using creosote (coal tar). Most of the woods used today for wooden crossties are hardwoods. Creosote not only acts as a preservative against decay, but it also helps to protect against wear of the crosstie acting as lubrication between the plate and tie.
 
A dual treatment is used to preserve wooden crossties in certain high decay areas. They are first treated with borate compounds, followed by creosote. Borates provide protection against decay while the crosstie is being air dried prior to treatment with creosote or other preservatives.

A gondola full of untreated railroad ties heading from a sawmill to a tie plant for processing. The wood crosstie has served the US railroad industry since its earliest days when wood ties were used as a foundation for the rail in the track structure. In 2018 the major US railroads installed a total of 13,778,638 ties. Smaller railroads installed a total of 2,366,845 ties for a total of 16,145,483 ties used by all US railroads in 2018.

Railroad Tie Lifespan
The climate zone of a railroad track determines the lifespan of a creosote-treated cross tie. There is more tie replacement maintenance work that occurs in a high decay areas. Railway tie manufacturers have been refining their processes for decades to increase the lifespan of wooden cross ties.
 
Although technological advances have led to crossties to made from concrete, steel, and plastic composites, wood ties still account for over 93% of railroad track applications.  Wood ties have been used since the mid-1800s, and after being treated with a wood preservative, they can last 30 years or more. Crossties support the vertical and lateral loads transmitted to the tie through the rails. Plus, wood is a renewable resource.
 
Just before the 1900s, tie manufacturers started using creosote (coal tar). Most of the woods used today for wooden crossties are hardwoods. Creosote not only acts as a preservative against decay, but it also helps to protect against wear of the crosstie acting as lubrication between the plate and tie.
 
A dual treatment is used to preserve wooden crossties in certain high decay areas. They are first treated with borate compounds, followed by creosote. Borates provide protection against decay while the crosstie is being air dried prior to treatment with creosote or other preservatives.

Railroad Tie Jenga?
A view of the untreated wood railroad tie curing yard at Koppers in Guthrie, Kentucky. The Koppers Guthrie plant was constructed by the L&N Railroad in 1912. The untreated products are trimmed and stacked, then air-dry in the tie yard for six to 12 months.
 
After the ties have reached the proper amount of curing, they are loaded on special flat cars and rolled into a large horizontal steel cylinder called a retort. After the retort is sealed, an initial vacuum pulls air from wood cells (initial air pressure is often used for railroad ties); the cylinder is flooded with liquid preservative; pressure pumps force the liquid into the wood replacing the air; at the completion of the process, excess preservative is drained from the cylinder for later reuse in the closed loop treating process; and wood is removed from the cylinder.

Kentucky Railroad Ties
The Koppers Guthrie plant was constructed by the L&N Railroad in 1912 at the intersection of its main line north and south/east and west. The plant was purchased by Koppers in 1958. Today, Guthrie is a primary supplier of crossties, switch ties and track panels to the CSX and national railroad systems. Koppers has been serving the railroad industry with treated wood railroad ties and railroad crossing panel products for more than 25 years. In North America, Koppers is the largest provider of railroad crossties for the Class I Railroads.

BNSF Northtown Yard
Classification yard tracks (the bowl) is where freight cars are sorted and assigned to departing trains in what is called a hump yard. The process begins when cars are pushed atop a small incline, or hump. Then gravity propels the car downward, with its speed controlled by a braking system consisting of a master retarder and secondary retarders. The yard averages of 1,500 cars a day at the 300-acre Northtown facility in Minneapolis.

Car weight, length of track to traverse and grade of the hump are calculated by a computer that then engages the braking system. This is so each car couples at approximately 4 mph in the bowl. Too fast could result in a derailed car; too slow could mean the car doesn’t reach the desired location. Multiple radar detectors and wheel detectors along the track monitor car speed so a secondary braking system can further slow them on their journey to the bowl tracks.

Note: video is speeded up 2x.

Pin Puller Scoreboard Display
View of the “Pin Puller” on the hump at BNSF Northtown Yard. Pin-puller displays are on either end of the pin-puller walkway. Software directs the Pin Puller on which cars are going to what track. 
 
The hump is a manmade hill over which railroad cars are pushed up by a locomotive. At the top of the hump, one or two switchmen work as pin pullers.  The pin pullers pull a device called a pin lifter on the side of a rail car. This uncouples cars from each other and allows them to move down the hump. The speed of the cars is controlled by retarders which are operated through a computer system and adjust the speed of the cars through a braking mechanism applied to the outside of the wheels. The cars are directed by computer into various tracks in what is called the "bowl." Cars going over the hump can be sent individually into various tracks or in groups of cars. Cars sent over the hump should couple automatically to the cars in the bowl.

Fun Fact: The pin puller is driving the train while uncoupling the cars using a Remote Control Operator (RCO) belt pack.

BNSF Northtown Yard
This site was the home of the old Northern Pacific yard in Minneapolis. The Burlington Northern was created by the merger of four railroads in 1970: the Great Northern Railway (GN), the Northern Pacific Railway (NP), the Spokane, Portland and Seattle Railway (SP&S) and the Chicago, Burlington and Quincy Railroad (CB&Q). The yard lies north of downtown Minneapolis, on the east side of the Mississippi, along the old NP line north to St. Cloud.
 
After the BN merger, BN Northtown Yard was built between 1971 and 1976, including a classification yard, engine house and car repair facility. Today, the 300-acre BNSF Northtown facility classifies an average of 1,500 cars a day 
 
• Receiving Yard: 12 receiving tracks
• Classification Yard: 53 classification tracks
• Departure Yard: 9 departure tracks

INTERMODAL HUMPING?
Sure. The 265’ long 5-unit well car goes over the hump at BNSF Northtown yard. Well cars are designed to carry intermodal shipping containers.
 
A string of cars is being pushed over the hump at the Northtown Yard in Minneapolis, Minnesota. A yard worker reads an electronic display that provides directions as they uncouple the cars and they roll down the hump. The computer operating the powered switches and “retarders” knows the weight of each car and sorts it to the proper track and controls the speed of the rolling car to prevent damage. Northtown is a classification yard that sorts cars to their destination, much like a post office sorts mail. The “bowl tracks” fan out from the hump in a series of automated switches, with each track representing a destination.

MOTHBALLED
BNSF’s Northtown yard in Minneapolis, Minnesota is one of several locations where BSNF stores locomotives to adjust to cyclic traffic demands driven by economic factors. Railroad fleet managers look at the age of locomotives, performance and reliability data of certain models, and the current needs of that particular locomotive type. The engines have been prepped my maintenance crews to prevent damage in storage.
 
BNSF had 2,500 locomotives “parked” as of the end of March 2020, out of a fleet of 8,000 locomotives.

St. Anthony Parkway Bridge
The original 533.6 foot, five-span, Warren through truss was built in 1925 and crosses over 24 tracks of the Burlington Northern Santa Fe Railyard. It is shown in the second photo as it was being demolished. The old bridge had one traffic lane in each direction and a sidewalk. The original St. Anthony Bridge was eligible for the National Register of Historic Places. The historic bridge was in dire need of replacement. The five-span truss bridge was not structurally redundant; if one element of the bridge’s truss spans were damaged or severed, the whole span could fail. Complicating matters, the non-redundant bridge spanned 21 BNSF Northtown Rail Yard tracks. The BNSF mainline around 50 trains per day. 
 
Careful design and coordination was required to replace the bridge while reflecting its history. The new bridge replaces the historic 85-year-old, five-span Warren truss bridge and features a 305 foot steel truss span and two-125 foot steel girder spans that carry two 12 foot lanes, a sidewalk and a bicycle trail over the BNSF yard. The bridge was designed by Short Elliott Hendrickson’s (SEH) bridge group in St. Paul. Major construction activities began in summer 2015 and were complete by February 2017.
 
Photo of old bridge from Mark Maves, leader of Short Elliott Hendrickson’s (SEH) bridge group.

Panel Track on a Flatcar
Railroads usually keep a wreck train at the ready in yards where track crews are stationed. This is a train equipped to clear tracks of debris or damaged equipment following a wreck or destruction by other means. Panel track is a primary tool in the arsenal used to quickly restore tracks that are damaged. Panel track is also increasing used for switch construction and other activities to save time. Anymore, wreck restoration work is frequently done by contractors like Hulcher Services, Inc. that offer specialized services for railroads.
 
By the 1950's, railroad operators had devised panel track for laying and/or repairing railroad tracks. A rail panel is made up of a pair of evenly spaced rails attached to a series of ties. In one standard configuration, the rail panel is 39 feet long and weighs approximately 10,000 pounds. The rails have joint bars on one end to allow the panel to be lined up with an existing section of track.
 
This flatcar with track panels in the BNSF Northtown Yard in Minneapolis. It is accompanied by ballast cars, gondolas with ties and various MOW equipment.

Inspection
An overhead shot of the BNSF Locomotive Shops in Minneapolis, Minnesota in 2019. Crew is working on BNSF 
1997 EMD SD40-2 built in 1978. The BNSF system locomotive shops to perform locomotive service and maintenance. After the BN merger, BN Northtown Yard was built between 1971 and 1976, including a classification yard, engine house and car repair facility.
 
Locomotives have to be inspected every calendar day they are in use, but that can be done by an engineer, RCO operator or mechanical crew. Locomotives go in for periodic inspections (by mechanical staff) every 92 or 184 days.  That's when they get a thorough going over, and usually come back with new brake shoes, filled fluids/sand, etc. Normally, they get fixed when they break. Some conditions require removal from service and immediate shopping, others can wait (depending on rules and laws).

Blue Signal Display
Railroads have blue flag/blue signal protection rules for employees to protect them while working on equipment. In the photo, you can see two blue flags on the locomotive. The blue flags are placed at right angles to the track, with one extends beyond the engine as on a car, and the other obstructa the engineer’s view from the cab.
 
Blue signals displayed in accordance with §§218.25, 27, or 29, signify that workers are on, under, or between railroad rolling equipment. When so displayed: The equipment may not be coupled to. The equipment may not be moved (see exceptions in §218.29).

Northtown Service Track
BNSF Northtown Diesel Shop Service Track in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Locomotives are required to be serviced and inspected, every 24 hours. Typically, a locomotive has a fuel capacity of 4,000 gallons of No. 2 Diesel and usually consumes 3.5 gallons of fuel per mile. Refueling is commonly done in a yard at a service rack. Refueling can take 5 min or half an hour depending on how much is needed and how good the pump is. In addition, the locomotives take on sand and water at a service rack.
 
At smaller facilities and at mainline sites, Direct Truck to Locomotive (DTL) fueling is performed by contracted fuel jobbers in an effort to reduce costs.

Turnaround Plan
A view of the turntable next to the BNSF Locomotive Shops in Minneapolis, Minnesota in 2020. The BNSF system locomotive shops to perform locomotive service and maintenance. After the BN merger, BN Northtown Yard was built between 1971 and 1976, including a classification yard, engine house and car repair facility.
 
Use of turntables to turn locomotives dates back to the 1830s. Turntables are still used as a convenient means for moving locomotives and other equipment onto tracks headed in the correct direction. Turntables are electrically operated from a control booth that is installed on the turntable. Although wye and balloon tracks can be used to turn an engine around, turntables require the least amount of space to do so. BNSF’s 32,500-mile rail network currently has 33 turntables in service, some dating back to the early 1900s.
 
At Northtown, a frequent use of the turntable is to orient the locomotives for service in the diesel shops.

Running Up That Hill
View of the “Pin Puller” remotely driving his train up the hump at BNSF Northtown Yard. Pin-puller displays are on either end of the pin-puller walkway. Software directs the Pin Puller on which cars are going to what track. 
 
The hump is a manmade hill over which railroad cars are pushed up by a locomotive. At the top of the hump, one or two switchmen work as pin pullers.  The pin pullers pull a device called a pin lifter on the side of a rail car. This uncouples cars from each other and allows them to move down the hump. The speed of the cars is controlled by retarders which are operated through a computer system and adjust the speed of the cars through a braking mechanism applied to the outside of the wheels. The cars are directed by computer into various tracks in what is called the "bowl." Cars going over the hump can be sent individually into various tracks or in groups of cars. Cars sent over the hump should couple automatically to the cars in the bowl.

Minneapolis Service Track
BNSF Northtown Diesel Shop Service Track in Minneapolis, Minnesota, on a rare day with no locomotives. This allows a look at the inspection pit under the Service Tracks. This was taken in October of 2020.
 
Locomotives are required to be serviced and inspected, every 24 hours. Typically, a locomotive has a fuel capacity of 4,000 gallons of No. 2 Diesel and usually consumes 3.5 gallons of fuel per mile. Refueling is commonly done in a yard at a service rack. Refueling can take 5 min or half an hour depending on how much is needed and how good the pump is. In addition, the locomotives take on sand and water at a service rack.
 
At smaller facilities and at mainline sites, Direct Truck to Locomotive (DTL) fueling is performed by contracted fuel jobbers in an effort to reduce costs.

BNSF Northtown Car Shops
Rules require that location where a freight car is placed in a train, the freight car be inspected before the train departs. This inspection may be made before or after the car is placed in the train. Freight car mechanics are referred to as a “carman”. Carmen perform air brake tests, schedule maintenance, and necessary inspections on locomotives and trains in accordance with federal regulations.

Railcars are put into Bad Order Status during the transport when the car requires any repair to running gear or safety appliances. These running gear parts and safety appliances are wheels, trucks, brakes, air hoses, draft gear, couplers, ladders, and platforms.

In BNSF Northtown yard, there is a freight car repair shop, seen here looking past the Canadian Pacific bridge over the yard. The classification yard tower and hump are on the upper left, car repair facility in the middle and the locomotive shops to the upper right. The modern facilities were built on the site of the old Northern Pacific yard in Minneapolis between 1971 and 1976.

BN Executive Paint Scheme Engines
This photo from September, 2012 show a pair EMD SD70MAC locomotives with an eastbound coal train on the BNSF Ottumwa Subdivision near Batavia, Iowa. BNSF 9973 on point with BNSF 9536 trailing, both EMD SD70MACs. BNSF 9301 EMD SD70ACe is pushing on the rear. Today, BNSF 9973 is scrapped and BNSF 9536 is retired.
 
In October 1990 the executive paint scheme was introduced on the Burlington Northern’s newly rebuilt F9 engines BN-1 and BN-2 and business car Stevens Pass. Also known as “Grinstein green” for Gerald Grinstein the president of BN, it was a departure from the standard BN colors. The color arrangement consists of Brunswick green on lower frame and upper hood with a crème band around the middle and accented with red pin stripe separating the two colors.
 
In 1993 BN placed an order with EMD for its new model, the SD70MAC painted in the Executive colors. Grinstein green continued through to BNSF with the company painting the final BN order of SD70MAC’s BNSF 9711-9837.
 
Eventually 428 SD70MAC’s the two F-9’s, one E-9 BN-3 (ex BN 9912), and the business car fleet would sport the unique colors.
 
This is a fading memory as in 2023, almost all of the Executive scheme SD70MACs are sold or retired, with one survior converted to a SD70MACe.

Slug Set for Hump
Two BNSF locomotives and a non-powered slug are used to push cars over the hump at the Northtown Yard in Minneapolis, Minnesota, seen in April, 2019. They are parked next to the hump tower, with the sound barriers on the retarders (used for hump braking) visible in the background.
 
BNSF 1988 EMD SD40-2 is in the foreground with BNSF 70 rebuilt EMD Slug and BNSF 1931 EMD SD40-2 at the far end. The slug was built in 1968 as Southern Pacific 5303 EMD SD39, then went to ATSF to be converted to a slug, and was rebuilt by BNSF.
 
A slug is usually an old locomotive rebuilt with no diesel power and cab. They are filled with concrete to add weight for traction. They get electrical power to operate its traction motors and motor controls from a fully-powered “mother”locomotive. 
 
A mother-slug takes advantage of the excess current that the mother's diesel-electric locomotive produces at low speed. This provides additional horsepower and braking at a lower cost tag a second locomotive.

Flagged for Inspection
BNSF 6594 GE ES44C4 at the BNSF Northtown Locomotive Shops in Minneapolis, Minnesota. Before mechanical work can begin, the engine needs to be secured to prevent any mishaps from moving a locomotive while maintenance workers are present.  Railroads have blue flag/blue signal protection rules for employees to protect them while working on equipment. In the photo, you can see two blue flags on the locomotive. The blue flags are placed at right angles to the track, with one extends beyond the engine as on a car, and the other obstruct the engineer’s view from the cab.
 
Blue signals displayed in accordance with §§218.25, 27, or 29, signify that workers are on, under, or between railroad rolling equipment. When so displayed: The equipment may not be coupled to. The equipment may not be moved (see exceptions in §218.29).

Locomotives are required to be serviced and inspected, every 24 hours. Typically, a locomotive has a fuel capacity of 4,000 gallons of No. 2 Diesel and usually consumes 3.5 gallons of fuel per mile. Refueling is commonly done in a yard at a service rack. Refueling can take 5 min or half an hour depending on how much is needed and how good the pump is. In addition, the locomotives take on sand and water at a service rack.

Now Replaced
Two BNSF locomotives and a non-powered slug are used to push cars over the hump at the Northtown Yard in Minneapolis, Minnesota, seen in April, 2019. They are parked next to the hump tower, with the sound barriers on the retarders (used for hump braking) visible in the background.
 
BNSF 1988 EMD SD40-2 is in the foreground with BNSF 70 rebuilt EMD Slug and BNSF 1769 EMD SD40-2 at the far end. The slug was built in 1968 as Southern Pacific 5303 EMD SD39, then went to ATSF to be converted to a slug, and was rebuilt by BNSF.
 
A slug is usually an old locomotive rebuilt with no diesel power and cab. They are filled with concrete to add weight for traction. They get electrical power to operate its traction motors and motor controls from a fully-powered “mother”locomotive.
 
A mother-slug takes advantage of the excess current that the mother's diesel-electric locomotive produces at low speed. This provides additional horsepower and braking at a lower cost tag a second locomotive.

Old Iron
Independent Locomotive Service (reporting mark ILSX) leases an ancient switcher to the Malt One Terminal in Minneapolis, Minnesota. ISLX 904 EMD SW1 is a 600hp relic that was built for Allis Chalmers in 1947, and lived a good portion of its service life in West Allis, Wisconsin.  Always amazes me that a 76-year-old locomotive is still in service.
 
The Elevator with the giant “MALT ONE” letters on the silos is a local landmark. The site is at CP Shoreham Yard. This was originally a Peavey Co. Elevator, that sold to Con Agra in 1982. Whitebox Commodities (Riverland Ag ) acquired the elevator in 2007, and sold it in 2010 to Ceres Global AG, the current owner. Canadian Pacific (CP) has a 55-car rail siding at the terminal.

Hostler

Railfanning + Beer
Beneath the twin stacks in the upper left is Forgotten Star Brewing Co in Fridley, MN is the BNSF Staples Sub at Milepost 14.55. This is adjacent to BNSF Northtown Yard. Steel-Highway also has a live stream web camera on Youtube so you can view the action on the BNSF mainline.
 
Forgotten Star is located in what used to be the boiler room for Northern Pump Company. The Northern Pump Company manufactured water pumps for fire fighting from 1929 to 1941, until the United States was forced to enter WWII.  Within months of the attack on Pearl Harbor, the facility was able to shift operations entirely and the first navy ship gun left the facility. Starting in October 1940, construction began on a new, 180,000 square foot facility in Fridley. Just 60 days later they moved in and began manufacturing in January 1941. The plant exploded from just 200 employees in 1938 to 12,000 in 1944.  The company produced naval gun mounts, pumps and ordnance.

CP Departure
Manifest freight departing Saint Paul Yard (Pig’s Eye) in 2021 heading toward Saint Paul. CP 8732 GE ES44AC (DRF-44) is on point with CP 9830 GE AC44CW (DRF-44) trailing. St. Paul Yard features 36 classification tracks and nine departure tracks, and six receiving tracks. The facility averages about 1,500 humped cars per day.
 
In 1951 a hump yard was built by the Milwaukee Road at Pigs Eye Lake, just south of Saint Paul. The yard went to Soo line when they assumed control of the ailing Milwaukee in 1985. The Soo Line Railroad, subsidiary of CPKC Railway, was named for the Minneapolis, St. Paul and Sault Ste. Marie Railroad (MStP&SSM). It was formed in 1961 by the consolidation of that company with two other CPKC subsidiaries: The Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway, and the Wisconsin Central Railway. Prior to the recent merger of Canadian Pacific and Kansas City Southern, the modern Canadian Pacific evolved in 2009. This is when CP acquired the Dakota, Minnesota and Eastern Railroad (DM&E) and the Iowa, Chicago and Eastern Railroad (IC&E). The trackage of the IC&E was at one time part of CP subsidiary Soo Line and predecessor line The Milwaukee Road.

The SD30C-ECO is variant in EMD's ECO repower catalog, launched by EMD in 2008.  The rebuilt locomotive receives a “rail up” rebuild. PIPE LOADS
Dayton's Bluff is a busy railroad junction in Minnesota's Twin Cities. The railroad tracks are between the Mississippi River and the mile-long Dayton's Bluff. Burlington Northern Santa Fe and the Canadian Pacific operate the tracks at Dayton’s Bluff, but every railroad that in the region pass through the Twin Cities on these tracks. Amtrak, Minnesota Commercial, Twin Cities and Western and Union Pacific use the tracks past Dayton Bluffs.
 
A 2019 photo shows a cut of pipe loads. Flat cars can carry almost anything, but these cars were purposely designed to carry pipe. Manufactured by American Car & Foundry, the 89' F-89-J Flat Cars were built in the late 1960's for intermodal service. By the 1990's, the Trailer Train Company had developed another use for these and other cars through the PTTX conversion program. Fitted with wood cross beams, the PTTX fleet was designed to accommodate pipe and bulk loads of varying diameter and weight. Featuring new, side mounted brake rigging and other PTTX specific details, these cars continue to roam the rails today carrying pipe and bulk loads of all kinds all over North America. BLMA (now Atlas) built excellent N and HO scale models of these cars.

Bumping Post
Union Depot in Saint Paul, Minnesota is one of America’s great rail stations from the early 20th century. Today, it is a major transportation in the heart of the Twin Cities. This is a photo of a “Hayes” Bumping Post at the end of a station siding.  Western-Cullen Hayes Bumping Posts are designed to stop movement beyond the end of a siding.
 
When properly installed at track ends, bumping posts engage the coupler and draft gear of a moving car and transfer the force of impact to ties, rail and ballast, bringing the car to a safe stop at normal switching speed.
 
How it works:
When a coupler strikes the Bumping Post the impact is taken in three directions:
1. Horizontal thrust along the track
2. Upward push at the front
3. Downward load at the rear
 
In all W-C-H Posts the horizontal thrust is carried to the track rails by alloy steel bolts having double the strength of ordinary bolts.

Cemstone Landmark
The concrete plant at Dayton’s Bluff is a landmark at this busy railroad junction. Cemstone has been family owned and operated for 5 Generations.  Hammon T. Becken founded the company in 1927. In the early days sand was dug by hand and sold by the bushel. Today they use high-tech methods of producing quality ready mixed concrete and aggregates.
 
The plant sits below the bluff next to CPKC Saint Paul Yard and BNSF Dayton’s Bluff yard.

Frac Sand Unit Train
The North Dakota oil boom not only has given railroads business transporting crude oil, but also a large amount of fracking sand. BNSF unit fracking sand train seen at Dayton Bluffs Yard in Saint Paul, Minnesota in 2021. BNSF 6351 GE ES44AC is on point with BNSF 4079 GE C44-9W trailing. BNSF 5837 GE ES44AC is the pusher in the rear of the train.
 
Industrial sand is a high purity silica historically sold for a variety of industries. Its most recent use is in the oil and gas recovery industry. Fracking of oil and gas has been the preferred method since about 2008 in North Dakota (the Bakken fields) shale drilling. Frac sand is a type of sand with small, uniform particles. It is injected into the rock formation along with the water used to fracture the rock in the process known as hydraulic fracturing ("fracking"). The sand is used to prop open the fractures that are created.

Great Western Ghost
Hoffman Yard in Saint Paul Minnesota was built by the Chicago Great Western Railroad.  In 1968, CGW merged into the Chicago and North Western in 1968, and then into the Union Pacific in 1995. The yard is between the CP Saint Paul Yard the Mississippi River, running alongside the river levee.
 
The current Union Pacific Railroad Albert Lea Subdivision from Des Moines, the former Rock Island "Spine Line", enters the Twin Cities area and terminates in a yard in South Saint Paul.
 
From this area, traffic to downtown St. Paul takes two routes: one across the Hoffman Swing Bridge, with yards on the east side of the river south of Dayton's Bluff; and the other route using the St. Paul Union Pacific Vertical-lift Rail Bridge into downtown St. Paul.

CP Saint Paul Yard Hump
A view of the hump in 2021 in Saint Paul, Minnesota. St. Paul Yard features 36 classification tracks and nine departure tracks, and six receiving tracks. The facility averages about 1,500 humped cars per day.
 
In 1951 a hump yard was built by the Milwaukee Road at Pigs Eye Lake, just south of Saint Paul. The yard went to Soo line when they assumed control of the ailing Milwaukee in 1985. The Soo Line Railroad, subsidiary of CPKC Railway, was named for the Minneapolis, St. Paul and Sault Ste. Marie Railroad (MStP&SSM). It was formed in 1961 by the consolidation of that company with two other CPKC subsidiaries: The Duluth, South Shore and Atlantic Railway, and the Wisconsin Central Railway. Prior to the recent merger of Canadian Pacific and Kansas City Southern, the modern Canadian Pacific evolved in 2009. This is when CP acquired the Dakota, Minnesota and Eastern Railroad (DM&E) and the Iowa, Chicago and Eastern Railroad (IC&E). The trackage of the IC&E was at one time part of CP subsidiary Soo Line and predecessor line The Milwaukee Road.

Iron Country
Minnesota’s iron ore operations have a production capacity of about 40 million tons of high-grade iron ore annually, which is approximately 75 percent of total U.S. iron ore production. Iron ore is mined from nine active mines and three reclamation operations in Michigan, Minnesota, and Utah. Most of the iron ore is mined in northern Minnesota's Mesabi Range.

The majority of the ore is transported by 13 thousand-foot ore boats on lakes Superior, Michigan, Huron and Erie. In addition, there are about 100 smaller lake freighters carrying various bulk cargoes. The remaining iron ore not shipped by boats are hauled by railroads.

The photos show BNSF ore trains in Northtown Yard in Minneapolis and at Dayton’s Bluff in St. Paul.

AC44C6M Rebuild
NS 4518 AC44C6M seen in Princeton, Indiana. The locomotive was rebuilt from NS 9336 Dash9W at the Juniata Shops.
 
In 2015, Norfolk Southern embarked on a program to rebuild an modernize it’s locomotive fleet. NS has been converting older D.C.-traction locomotives into A.C.-traction units at a pace of about 100 locomotives per year. In 2022, NS place their third multi-year order with Wabtec to modernize 330 more locomotives. By 2025, they will have modernized 950 locomotives.
 
The AC44C6M retains the 16-cylinder 7FDL-16 prime mover used in the core locomotive prior to rebuilding, but replace the Dash 9's DC traction motors with alternating current GE 5GEB13B7 traction motors. Externally, the rebuilds have received new wide-nosed cabs, a new front hood section, and a new inverter cabinet behind the cab, while retaining the underframe and engine and radiator compartments of the original Dash 9 units.
 
Rebuilding an old Dash 9 locomotive into an AC44C6M costs only 50-60% that of purchasing a new AC locomotive. The  D9-44CW locomotives rebuilt in the program are over 20 years old.  Transforming them into AC44C6Ms adds another 20 years of incremental life to each locomotive.

Distributed Power
Northbound CSX freight on the CSX CE&D Subdivision (Chicago, Evansville and Danville) seen in Princeton, Indiana. CSX 3202 GE ES44AC-H is on point with mid-train distributed power CSX 856 GE ES44AC.
 
Increased train length contributes to a significant reduction in the number of trains operated on a daily basis. Over the last several decades freight railroads have developed the use of distributed power by using sophisticated onboard software and communications technology. Placing DPUs throughout the train rather than just at the rear distributes power more evenly. This allows railroads to run fewer, longer trains.
 
The AAR estimates 99% of trains are under 14,000 feet. That 99th percentile has increased over the past decade — up from about 10,000 feet in 2010. 50% of freight trains are between 5,400 feet and 14,000 feet long. Despite a median length of about 1 mile, 50% of trains are over 1 mile long today.

Indiana Coal Country
In 2020, Indiana used about four-fifths of its mined coal in-state and shipped most of the rest to almost a dozen other states by rail, barge, and truck. Indiana annually is eighth of the top ten coal producing states in the nation averaging 32,000,000 to 35,000,000 tons each year (EIA). Most is produced by 12-15 companies from approximately 24 active operations in ten southwestern Indiana counties. Until recently, more than 95 percent of electricity used in Indiana came from coal. Today, the Indiana electric utilities are lowering their reliance on coal, and adding solar and gas generating capacity to reduce greenhouse gas emissions.

Princeton Diamond
The ten counties in southwestern Indiana are generally known for “black diamonds” as a big coal producing region. A busy railroad diamond is in Princeton, Indiana, where the CSX mainline from Chicago to Nashville crosses the Norfolk Southern Mainline from Louisville to St. Louis. 
 
The Norfolk Southern line through Princeton, Indiana is the former Southern Railway mainline from Louisville to Saint Louis. The “Southern Line” is made of two Districts meeting at Princeton: East & West. CSX’s CE&D Subdivision (Chicago, Danville & Evansville) crosses the NS just west of the yard, and the two lines run parallel through Princeton for a little over 2 miles.
 
With the two lines sharing a right of way through Princeton, it makes for a unique diamond.

Rail Loop Serving CSX & NS
In 2019 the Alliance – Gibson County Coal Rail Load-out Facility went into production. This is ideal for the shipper as it allow access to both CSX and Norfolk Southern rail networks which greatly extends their customer opportunities. 
 
Alliance is the 2nd-largest coal producer in the eastern United States. The mine in Gibson County is one of five mines operated by Alliance in the Illinois Basin Coal Deposit. Gibson County Coal, LLC operates the Gibson South Mine, located near the city of Princeton in Gibson County, Indiana. Gibson South is an underground mine and utilizes continuous mining units employing room-and-pillar mining techniques to produce low/medium-sulfur coal. The Gibson South mine's preparation plant has a throughput capacity of 1,800 tons of raw coal per hour. Gibson South in Indiana began production in April of 2014. Gibson North Coal Mine has been inactive since November 2019. 
 
The coal loadout facility is located 6 miles West of Princeton, IN on Highway 64 and includes the ability to unload trucks, blend coals, load 135 car unit trains in four hours and store over 4 million tons of coal.

Coal Loading Terminal
The Alliance - Gibson County Coal / Rail Load-out Facility is all about logistics.  This coal loadout has a very tight schedule to assure the electric power plants that rely on it get their coal on time. Low coal stockpiles at a its coal-fired power plants can force a utility to curtail generation, which is a very expensive issue. A large "unit train" of coal can contain 130-140 cars with around 100 tons of coal per car, for a total load of over 10,000 tons. A large plant under full load requires at least one coal delivery this size every day. Large plants may get as many multiple trains a day in "peak season" during the hottest summer or coldest winter months when power consumption is high.
 
The loadout loop is designed to be able to juggle loaded and empty trains. There is a very structured logistic schedule, so there is pressure to get trains in and out efficiently. The electric power plants do maintain a small buffer of coal to protect against delivery issues, but space and economic considerations limit how much coal can be stockpiled.
 
In 2019 the Alliance – Gibson County Coal Rail Load-out Facility went into production. This is ideal for the shipper as it allow access to both CSX and Norfolk Southern rail networks which greatly extends their customer opportunities.

Loads and Empties
After entering the loadout loop from either the CSX of the NS mainlines in Princeton, Indiana, then the fun begins. The empty trains have to loop around the site to get into position on the inner flood loading track. Flood loading-coal from the silo into the cars-probably takes around hour by the time the movements take place. Specialized software in the locomotives allows for fine slow speed control required for flood loading. AC locomotives are best for heavy loaded coal trains because they can pull harder at lower speeds and can't burn out there traction motors ( a weakness with DC motors). After loading, they move to the outer tracks for movement onto the mainline.

GEVO
CN 3035 GE GE ETAC44AC in South Bend, Indiana.

Canadian National has 286 GE ET44AC locomotives in their roster, numbered 3000–3285. The Evolution Series is a line of diesel locomotives built by GE Transportation Systems (now owned by Wabtec), initially designed to meet the U.S. EPA’s Tier 2 locomotive emissions standards that took effect in 2005. The first pre-production units were built in 2003. Evolution Series locomotives are equipped with either AC or DC traction motors, depending on the customer’s preference. All are powered by the GE GEVO engine.
 
ET44AC/ET44C4 (2012-Present)
The ET44AC (Evolution Series Tier 4, 4,400 hp, AC traction) replaces the ES44AC model. These locomotives have been ordered by most of the Class I railroads in North America, including Union Pacific, CSX Transportation, Norfolk Southern and Canadian National Railway. BNSF Railway will be receiving similar ET44C4 locomotives, which have no traction motor on the middle axle of each truck. CSX designates their ET44ACs as ET44AH, due to their locomotives being heavy-ballasted.

Car Loading Rules
You might have noticed when a freight train rolls by the ground shakes. A train can weigh anywhere from 4,000 tons to as much as 20,000 tons. One rail car can hold three to four truckloads worth of freight. Most freight cars can have a gross weight (the total weight of the load, including the weight of the rail car itself) of up to 286,000 pounds. Heavy axle rail cars can have a gross weight of up to 315,000 pounds.
 
Isaac Newton observed: Objects in motion tend to stay in motion. If a train starts or stops, the freight car loads have to stay on the car. That is why the securement of freight car loads is regulated by rules. They are actually engineered and tested to ensure that commodities are loaded on freight cars in a safe, efficient and economical manner is a critical part of the transportation process.
 
I caught a photo of a gondola with a pipe load in South Bend, Indiana. The diagram shows the proper way to secure the pipe load according to the Car Loading Rules guidelines. These are developed and maintained by the Association of American Railroads and Railway Association of Canada. The Rule Book defines engineered loading procedures for all open cars and load types. “Shippers must comply with carriers’ rules regulating safe loading of freight and protection of equipment.”

PARKED
NS 4420 tied up on a siding on the CNO&TP 3nd District by the DeButts Yard in Chattanooga, Tenneessee. 
 
This locomotive was rebuilt from GE Dash 9-44CW NS 9204, originally built in 04-1998. In February 2021 it was rebuilt by Wabtec in Ft. Worth, Texas into a AC44C6M, converting the traction motors from DC to AC. The unit is painted in standard NS black & white “horsehead” scheme.
 
The DC to AC rebuild program started in 2015, and upon completion in 2025, more than 950 locomotives will l have been rebuilt. Converting older DC-traction locomotives to AC traction increases fuel efficiency and reduces carbon emissions. This initiative is the ultimate recycling project and involves taking older locomotives and stripping them down to the steel frame and outfitting them with new engines, traction motors, and the latest technology. AC traction motors are more efficient, have lower maintenance costs and higher tractive effort. Better traction means that the locomotives can pull more weight with fewer locomotives, further driving fuel efficiency. With the addition of distributed power technology, the locomotives can be in other positions besides the front of the train. This creats greater fuel efficiency as well as improved train handling.

NS DeButts Yard
The hump yard in Chattanooga was shut down in 2017. The yard then served as a block-swapping facility. After the closures, the railroad struggled to operate minus key hump yards, so the hump yard in Chattanooga resumed operations by the end of 2018. The hump remained completely intact but the retarders were removed. The retarders, devices that slow cars on their descent into the classification bowl had to be re-installed. DeButts remained busy as a flat switching classification yard, block swapping location, and engine shop. Due to a surge in traffic, dismal terminal dwell times, and overall slower transit times in the southeast, NS decided to reopen the hump at DeButts.
 
Norfolk Southern’s active hump yards are in Elkhart, Indiana; Conway and Enola, Pennsylvania.; Chattanooga, Tennessee; and Birmingham, Alabama. In 2022, Norfolk Southern resumed hump operations at its classification yards in Macon, Ga., and Bellevue, Ohio. Both yards were converted to flat-switching facilities in 2020 after volume sank at the onset of the pandemic.

Over the Hump
A string of empty autoracks go over the hump at DeButts Yard in Chattanooga, Tenneessee. Note to the right of the autoracks by the yard tower racks is “pin-puller”. This was taken in September 2023.
 
NS's Debutts Yard reopened in 2018 with a unique "hybrid" configuration that combines flat-switching with humping. The yard is named for former Southern Railway President Harry A. DeButts, (from 1952 to 1962).
 
Debutts Yard now consists of 60 tracks arranged in seven groups: four groups of nine tracks for humping, three groups of eight tracks for flat-switching, at the pull-out end. The hump classifies cars for local customers; the flat-switch section is used mainly for block swapping, to make up new trains that are pulled out into the departure yards. The hump throughput capacity at DeButts Yard is now 800 to 1,000 cars per day.

Classification Bowl
A view of the destination sorting tracks at Norfolk Southern DeButts Yard in Chattanooga, Tenneessee. Hump yards, also known as classification yards, have three parts: the receiving yard, the classification bowl and the departure yard. A manifest train carrying mixed freight enters the receiving area and prepares for sorting by climbing a small artificial hill on the lead track. At the crest of the hill, a yard worker then uncouples from the train a single car or a block of cars that are intended for a specific destination track. Each track in the classification bowl is for a destination.  Specialized computer software directs the car to the proper destination track. NS's Debutts Yard is a unique "hybrid" configuration that now combines flat-switching with humping. The yard is named for former Southern Railway President Harry A. DeButts, (from 1952 to 1962).

Debutts Yard now consists of 60 tracks arranged in seven groups: four groups of nine tracks for humping, three groups of eight tracks for flat-switching, at the pull-out end. The hump classifies cars for local customers; the flat-switch section is used mainly for block swapping, to make up new trains that are pulled out into the departure yards. The hump throughput capacity at DeButts Yard is now 800 to 1,000 cars per day.

SERVICE
Norfolk Southern Chattanooga Locomotive Shop
 
Locomotives have to be inspected every calendar day they are in use, but that can be done by an engineer, RCO operator or mechanical crew. Locomotives go in for periodic inspections (by mechanical staff) every 92 or 184 days.  That's when they get a thorough going over, and usually come back with new brake shoes, filled fluids/sand, etc. Normally, they get fixed when they break. Some conditions require removal from service and immediate shopping, others can wait (depending on rules and laws).

NS Chattanooga 
The Norfolk Southern diesel shops in Chattanooga have been a landmark for decades. The Chattanooga diesel shop was the third one built exclusively for diesel work by Southern Railway. The first shop was a traction motor repair shop at Atlanta which was opened in 1944, then opened a Diesel shop at Alexandria in July 1945. Southern spent millions of dollars in building or converting shop facilities for diesel maintenance and repair since their first freight diesel went in service in 1941.

Locomotive Storage
Norfolk Southern Chattanooga Diesel Shop is one of the locations they maintain their locomotive fleet. According to NS's 2022 Annual Report, at the end of 2022 they had 3,190 locomotives. The locomotives are roughly 75 feet long and weigh about 216 tons. Norfolk Southern said the locomotives last on average about 30 years, but as advances in technology increase, so will the lifespan of the trains. This 2019 photo shows a string of locomotives stored at the facility.

Acid Tank Cars
Hydrochloric Acid Tank cars at the Norfolk Southern Debutts Yard in Chattanooga, Tennessee in February 2023. I have an Athearn HO scale model of this RCRX tank car, so I love it when I can take a prototype photo of a model I have.
 
RCRX is the reporting mark of Reagent Chemical and Research, Inc. headquartered in Ringoes, New Jersey. The current RCRX railcar fleet consists of non-insulated DOT class 111A100W5 rubber lined tank cars used primarily for the transport of hydrochloric acid. Reagent is the largest supplier of liquid hydrochloric acid in North America. They have more than 3,000 rubber lined railcars — the largest HCl fleet in North America. The tank cars designed specifically for the safe and efficient transport of Hydrochloric acid (HCl). 
 
Hydrochloric acid, also known as muriatic acid, is an aqueous solution of hydrogen chloride (HCl). It is a clear, colorless solution with a distinctive pungent odor. Hydrochloric acid is used in the production of other industrial chemicals, food and steel processing, water treatment and energy production. Reagent Chemical markets hydrochloric acid produced from by-product and burner producers. Hydrogen chloride or hydrochloric acid is produced by burning hydrogen and chlorine together and is also a by-product of the chlorination of organic compounds. The concentration and the quality of HCl are the decisive factors for the type of application.

NS Chattanooga
NS's Debutts Yard is a unique "hybrid" configuration that combines flat-switching with humping. The yard is named for former Southern Railway President Harry A. DeButts, (from 1952 to 1962).
 
Debutts Yard now consists of 60 tracks arranged in seven groups: four groups of nine tracks for humping, three groups of eight tracks for flat-switching, at the pull-out end. The hump classifies cars for local customers; the flat-switch section is used mainly for block swapping, to make up new trains that are pulled out into the departure yards. The hump throughput capacity at DeButts Yard is now 800 to 1,000 cars per day.

Coffey's Cliff
In Chattanooga, the cliff is a nice spot to watch Norfolk Southern and CSXT, plus you get a good view of the North Boyce signal on CSX. It is on the north end of NS's DeButts Yard. You'll see plenty of NS freights going in and out of the yard, plus plenty of yard moves. Almost non-stop action. CSX's mainline parallels the yard on the east side, directly below Coffey's Cliff's vantage point. Stuart St. dead ends at this location. When you go to Coffey's Cliff take a friend, as that part of town is “interesting”, and definitely don't go there at night.

Receiving Yard
A look at the receiving yard where inbound trains wait to be sorted over the hump. Some trains are not classified, but exchange blocks of cars using flat switching. A “block” is a group of cars going to a particular destination. Switch crews will switch cars arriving on an inbound train to the proper outbound train. NS's Debutts Yard reopened in 2018 with a unique "hybrid" configuration that combines flat-switching with humping.
 
The yard is named for former Southern Railway President Harry A. DeButts, (from 1952 to 1962). Debutts Yard now consists of 60 tracks arranged in seven groups: four groups of nine tracks for humping, three groups of eight tracks for flat-switching, at the pull-out end. The hump classifies cars for local customers; the flat-switch section is used mainly for block swapping, to make up new trains that are pulled out into the departure yards. The hump throughput capacity at DeButts Yard is now 800 to 1,000 cars per day.

LOOKOUT
Lookout Mountain is the backdrop for Norfolk Southern’s DeButts Yard. Lookout Mountain rises 2,000 feet above sea level and overlooks Chattanooga. The attractions that call Lookout Mountain home: Rock City, Ruby Falls, the Incline Railway and Chickamauga & Chattanooga National Military Park.
 
Lookout Mountain was the scene of the 18th-century battle during the Nickajack Expedition. On November 24, 1863, during the American Civil War, the Battle of Lookout Mountain took place here. During the Civil War, the Confederate army held Lookout Mountain until 1863. In November, following the Union's defeat at Chickamauga, General Joseph Hooker's army stormed up the mountainside.

Mother-Slug
Norfolk Southern “mother-slug” seen pulling out a string of cars from the NS DeButts Yard classification.  NS 738 Rebuilt EMD RP-E4C (SOU 7067 EMD GP50) “yard slug” it’s “mother” NS 3073 EMD GP40-2 trailing. A slug is usually an old locomotive rebuilt with no diesel power and cab. They are filled with concrete to add weight for traction. They get electrical power to operate its traction motors and motor controls from a fully-powered “mother” locomotive. A mother-slug takes advantage of the excess current that the mother's diesel-electric locomotive produces at low speed. This provides additional horsepower and braking at a lower cost tag a second locomotive.

Passing a Ghost
The switch in the lower left leads to what once was the Pere Marquette New Buffalo Yard. Chicago Main lines for the Michigan Central and Pere Marquette ran through New Buffalo. The Pere Marquette had a coaling station here which still straddles CSX main line. The yard was also a junction point for a PM branch line south into Indiana and LaPorte. A 1970 USGS Map shows the yard in 1970 on the second frame.
 
CSX C800 loaded coal train on the CSX Grand Rapids Subdivision in New Buffalo, Michigan. BNSF 6261 GE ES44AC is on point. BNSF 8567 is EMD SD70ACe pushing on the rear. The CSX Grand Rapids Sub ends at Porter, Indiana. Trackage rights have always been used west of Porter on the former New York Central line, as far as Pine Jct. where it moves back to the former B&O. The train is CSX C800 - Cicero, IL (BNSF) to West Olive, MI (J. H. Campbell Plant).

Carbon Black Hopper
Sid Richardson Carbon hopper SRCX 5041 seen in Chattanooga, Tennessee in 2018. Sid Richardson Carbon has three plants in the U.S., two in Texas, one in Louisiana and a research facility in Fort Worth. In 2018 Tokai Carbon Co. Ltd acquired Fort Worth-based Sid Richardson Carbon Ltd.
 
The carbon black production in the oil and gas industry is a little known but important industrial chemical. The majority of the US carbon black production is in the Permian Basin in Texas. This was a really dirty industry, but today the only discernable discharge from the plant would be that small plume of whitish steam-like smoke that contains little or no particulate material going into the atmosphere.
 
This car was of interest to me as I have a “near equivalent” HO model of the car produced by Atlas. The ACF Industries 100-ton 4,650-cubic-foot Center Flow covered hopper was produced in three numbers. The Atlas models represent the most common prototypes which were built starting in mid-1966 and remain in production. Scale Trains also a model of the Thrall 4727 cubic foot carbon black covered hopper which stared production n 1992.
 
The most common use (70%) of carbon black is as a pigment and reinforcing phase in automobile tires. Its low cost makes it a common addition to cathodes and anodes and is considered a safe replacement to lithium metal in lithium-ion batteries. About 20% of world production goes into belts, hoses, and other non-tire rubber goods. The remaining 10% use of carbon black comes from pigment in inks, coatings, and plastics.

Chattanooga Diesel Shops
The Norfolk Southern diesel shops in Chattanooga have been a landmark for decades. The Chattanooga diesel shop was the third one built exclusively for diesel work by Southern Railway. The first shop was a traction motor repair shop at Atlanta which was opened in 1944, then opened a Diesel shop at Alexandria in July 1945. Southern spent millions of dollars in building or converting shop facilities for diesel maintenance and repair since their first freight diesel went in service in 1941.

Locomotive Wash
A view of a Norfolk Southern locomotive wash facility (NS Photo). I took photos of the NS South Wash being constructed in 2013. The other photos show the completed facility and the NS Debutts Yard wastewater treatment plant.
 
The wash facility is just one part of a complex system of industrial wastewater management system to comply with environmental regulations. Systemwide, NS has over 150 water discharge permits in place that govern the quality of water discharges from NS facilities and protect the environment. Wastewater treatment plants handle industrial wastewater generated by railyard activities, such as locomotive oil changes and exterior washes, use of industrial lubricants from locomotive repair shops, and locomotive coolants.
 
The Norfolk Southern DeButts facility is responsible for capturing and treating all of the industrial wastewater runoff at this site where rail cars that typically carry coal, petroleum and chemicals are brought to be cleaned and maintained.
 
The locomotive wash shop has a three-tier wash bay equipped with two work platforms with high-pressure hot water and an engine exhaust-venting system. With the additional work platform, employees can clean the top of locomotives. The exhaust vent lets them wash dirt, snow, and ice off a locomotive’s trucks and traction motors, which can be cleaned only when the engine is running.

Chattanooga National Cemetery
A view of the cemetery behind Norfolk Debutts Yard in 2013. The cemetery was established in 1863, by an order from Major General George Henry Thomas after the Civil War Battles of Chattanooga, as a place to inter Union soldiers who fell in combat. 75 acres of land was initially appropriated from two local land owners, but later purchased. It became Chattanooga National Cemetery in 1867. By 1870 more than 12,000 interments had been made, most of whom were unknown.
 
Locomotives parked in the yard are NS 6938 rebuilt EMD SD60E, NS 2628 EMD SD70M, NS 2564 EMD SD70 and NS 2501 SD70.

EMD SD75 Fest
BNSF 268 EMD SD75M and BNSF 277 EMD SD75I on a northbound empty trash train parked in BNSF Boeing Field Yard in Seattle, Washington.  The EMD SD75M and EMD SD75I were produced by EMD from 1994 to 1996. They were an enhancement to the EMD SD70s that increased engine power from 4,000 to 4,300 horsepower. They were a competitive response to General Electric’s Dash 9-44CW locomotives, aiming to provide increased power and advanced features. 

The “M” designation in the model name signifies the use of the North American style cab. The “I” model, referred to the “Isolated Cab”. The design reduces noise and vibration within the cab to make conditions better for the crew. 

ATSF purchased 51 SD75M locomotives. ATSF Road Numbers 200–250, later BNSF 8200–8250, and then back to 200–250). Units 202, 209, 218, 222, 225, 229, and 230 were transferred to Norfolk Southern as 2800–2806. Others were sold to PRLX. 

After the ATSF and BN merged to form BNSF, 26 SD75I were purchased. (Road Numbers 8276–8301). Units 8276–8299 were renumbered to 276–299, and 8300–8301 were renumbered to 249–250. These were delivered in 1997.

TRASHY!
BNSF H-INBROO Priority train, Interbay Yard Seattle to Roosevelt, WA returning with empty containers after “taking out the trash”. BNSF 4447 is on point with BNSF 7424 trailing as the train is parked along Elliot Bay just south of Balmer Yard (Interbay).

The trains go down the Seattle Sub to Vancouver, Washington, and turn up the Columbia River gorge to Roosevelt, Washington. The garbage travels over 300 miles from its origin to the landfill. Specialized double stack containers are used with a tops made from rubberized fabric that can be rolled up at one end of the container for easy unloading. When they get to Roosevelt, the containers are put on trucks and driven up the hill to the landfill.

Pipeline on Rails
BNSF unit oil train parked in Boeing Field Yard, carrying oil from Montana. The reporting mark PPRX on the tank cars indicate they belong to Phillips Petroleum. They are heading to the Ferndale Refinery, located on Puget Sound in Ferndale, Washington, approximately 20 miles south of the U.S.-Canada border. These tank are a safer type of tank car, the DOT-117, which has various features that make it less likely to break open in an accident and more resistant to heat damage in a fire. U.S. Rail carriers that transport Bakken crude and other Class 3 flammable liquids in Washington use only DOT-117 cars or other cars that meet even higher safety standards.
 
The train has two locomotives in the front and two in the rear, with buffer cars on either side to protect the tank cars.
 
BNSF 5914 GE ES44AC is on point with BNSF 5477 GE Dash 9-44CW trailing.
 
BNSF 6873 GE ES44C4 and GE Dash 9-44CW are distributed power on the rear. 
 
Washington state sees millions of gallons of crude oil move by rail through the state each week, coming from North Dakota and Alberta, Canada. The state has the fifth highest oil refining capacity of any state. As of 2018, there are 5 refineries in Washington state with a joint capacity of 637,700 b/d. The mountainous geography isolate Washington State from national pipeline networks, so the local refineries are critical to providing petroleum production for the Pacific Northwest.

Prepping for Departure
AMTK 313 Siemens Charger ALC-42 is on point as the Seattle section Train 8 is pulled from the Amtrak coach yard to Kings Street Station to prep for an on time departure. Trains 7 and 27 are the same train from Chicago to Spokane; cars separate to go to Seattle and Portland. Trains 8 and 28 join at Spokane to become the same train from Spokane to Chicago.

After westbound train 7 arrives Seattle, it heads just south of the Amtrak facilities and is turned around on a wye to become Train 8 eastbound. It goes into the Amtrak yard for servicing and inspection before continuing on its return trip to Chicago.
 
The Empire Builder is an Amtrak long-distance passenger train that operates daily between Chicago and either Seattle or Portland via two sections west of Spokane. The train was the premier passenger train of the Great Northern Railway and began service in 1929. The overall journey Chicago to Seattle is over 2200 miles and takes about 46 hours.

Sounder Commuter Rail
SDRX 902 EMD F59PHI (built 1999) parked next to T-Mobile Park, a retractable roof stadium, in Seattle, Washington. 

Sounder commuter rail uses diesel-powered locomotives and multi-level passenger coach trains that run mostly on BNSF Railway Company railroad freight tracks. Sounder shares the tracks with freight trains and Amtrak passenger trains, using upgraded signals, switches, and street crossings. Sounder commuter rail owns 67 rail cars (27 cab cars, 40 coach cars) manufactured by Bombardier and 14 EMD locomotives. Sound Transit contracts with BNSF to operate its Sounder service and with Amtrak for maintenance of the fleet. Maintenance activities are carried out at Amtrak’s Holgate yard in Seattle’s SODO District.
 
The Sounder has a sister service, Link light rail, which is an electrically-powered service that adds a system of high-capacity transportation within the region’s highest employment and transit ridership areas.

Going Under Seattle

Amtrak Seattle Shops
Washington is home to Amtrak’s Seattle Maintenance Facility. This complex maintains and services the remaining 2 Talgo train sets, 15 locomotives and 23 passenger cars some of which are Sound Transit fleet and some Amtrak Cascades. The facility also performs turnaround servicing for two daily National Network trains.

2012 marked the completion of the first two of the four phase project. Last winter the materials storage and office building opened. Phase two is the maintenance building for the Talgo trainsets used on the Cascades and the Sounder cars Amtrak maintains under contract with Sound Transit.

The maintenance building contains two tracks long enough to accommodate a full Talgo trainset. Below grade inspection pits run nearly the length of each track. The building also contains facilities and office space for the people that work in the facility. The first two phases cost $37 million.

In 2017, Amtrak awarded a $34-million contract to construct the locomotive service and repair facility in Seattle. This facility was completed in 2019. These buildings house a locomotive servicing facility and a maintenance facility for the Superliner equipment used on the Empire Builder and Coast Starlight.

Amtrak Dash 8
AMTRK 506 GE B32-8WH parked at the Amtrak’s Seattle Maintenance Facility in Seattle, Washington. This engine was part of an order of 20 locomotives in 1991 numbered Amtrak 500-519. The B32-8WH is based on GE’s Dash 8 series of freight train locomotives. They were the first locomotives purchased to replace the veteran Amtrak EMD F40PH.
 
They locomotives were nicknamed “Pepsi Cans” by many railfans, due to being delivered in a wide-striped red, white, and blue livery. Since the most recent overhauls, the locomotives now wear the Phase V livery. The B32-8WHs have been displaced by the newer and more powerful GE Genesis and Siemens Charger, and have been relegated to yard switching. The Dash–8s occasionally substitute for the Genesis and Charger units if necessary.

Seattle Harbor Rail Network
Two Class 1 railroads serve the Puget Sound region: the BNSF Railway (formerly Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railroad) and the Union Pacific Railroad (UPRR). The Port of Seattle is one of the nation’s largest container ports and a critical US international trade gateway. It’s the 4th largest distribution center network in the U.S. and one of fastest rail transport routes to Chicago of any West Coast port.
 
The UPRR mainline terminates at Argo Yard in the southeast portion of the Duwamish industrial area. The yard is made up of multiple storage and loading tracks. Trackage rights allow for UPRR operations over BNSF owned track connecting to the Port’s T5 and Terminal 18.
 
In the Seattle Industrial District, the north-south BNSF track connects to the north end of Argo Yard at the Coach wye5. The west leg of the wye skirts the north end of Argo Yard and turns north into the Seattle International Gateway (SIG) Intermodal Facility. The SIG has multiple storage and loading tracks that serve off-terminal containerized train traffic from the Port and other local customers.
 
Source: Seattle Department of Transportation study-funds application

Former Pere Marquette
Seen here is CSX M326 runs daily from Chicago Barr Yard to Grand Rapids, Michigan at the WE KIRK Siding near Watervlirt, Michigan. M326 and M327 are the manifest freights that run west on the Grand Rapids Sub, running from from Barr yard in Chicago to Grand Rapids and back.
 
This manifest freight has a variety of cars, lead by CSX 3133 GE ET44AH. CSX designates their ET44ACs as ET44AH, due to their locomotives being heavy-ballasted for High Tractive Effort. This is one of a group of 225 ET44AH Evolution Series Tier 4, 4400 HP, AC traction locomotive purchased by CSX in 2016-2017.  CSX 5244 GE ES40DC is the DPU power on the rear of the train.
 
The 136 mile CSX Grand Rapids Subdivision is the former Pere Marquette Railroad (Chesapeake & Ohio Railway - Chicago Subdivision). Originally constructed in 1870-1872 from New Buffalo to Grand Rapids by Chicago & Michigan Lake Shore Railroad then extended to Porter Indiana in 1903. Trackage rights have always been used west of Porter on the former New York Central line, as far as Pine Junction.

Getting Loaded!
SANY loaded container handler in Union Pacific’s Argo Yard in Seattle, Washington. The UPRR mainline terminates at Argo Yard in the southeast portion of the Duwamish industrial area. The yard is made up of multiple storage and loading tracks. Trackage rights allow for UPRR operations over BNSF owned track connecting to the Port’s T5 and Terminal 18.
 
Two Class 1 railroads serve the Puget Sound region: the BNSF Railway (formerly Burlington Northern and Santa Fe Railroad) and the Union Pacific Railroad (UPRR). The Port of Seattle is one of the nation’s largest container ports and a critical US international trade gateway. It’s the 4th largest distribution center network in the U.S. and one of fastest rail transport routes to Chicago of any West Coast port.

Northwest Seaport Alliance
The Northwest Seaport Alliance, which includes the marine cargo operations of the ports of Seattle and Tacoma, is the fourth-largest container gateway in the United States. The NWSA also manages breakbulk, auto and bulk terminals and handled nearly 3.4 million TEUs and over 24.4 million tons of other cargo in 2021. Approximately half the import cargo that moves through the NWSA gateway is bound for destinations outside of the Puget Sound region, primarily the Midwest. The $500 million Terminal 5 modernization will allow the NWSA to handle some of the largest container vessels calling at West Coast ports today. As container vessels in the 14,000 TEU size regularly call at terminals in the North and South harbors, modernization of Terminal 5 will allow for vessels up to 18,000 TEU.
 
A major investment was made in the Port of Seattle terminal 5 to support super post-panamax ships in Seattle’s North Harbor. Standing 96.3 meters tall with a 73.15 meters outreach boom, each crane can handle vessels with containers stacked 10 high and 25 wide on deck, providing increased capacity and job opportunities for the region and will be among the largest cranes along the West Coast.
 
Four Super Post-Panamax cranes that arrived at Terminal 5 in 2021. Two additional Super Post-Panamax cranes for Terminal 5 cranes arrived in 2023 and will begin moving cargo at the beginning of 2024. The six cranes and the completion of the South Berth expansion will enable two vessels to berth at Terminal 5 increasing cargo throughput.

NS Chicago Line
NS ET44AC GE ES44AC leads a westbound manifest freight near New Carlisle, Indiana moving at track speed on the Norfolk Southern Chicago Line. NS 4533 rebuilt GE AC44c6M is trailing.
 
The Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway, established in 1833, was a major part of the New York Central Railroad’s Water Level Route from Buffalo, New York, to Chicago, Illinois, primarily along the south shore of Lake Erie and across northern Indiana.  In 1998, its ownership was split at Cleveland, Ohio, between CSX Transportation to the east and Norfolk Southern Railway in the west. Now from Cleveland, west to Chicago, the line is known as Norfolk Southern’s Chicago Line.

Daily Steel Coil Train
The Cleveland-Cliffs Tek and Kote facility in New Carlisle, Indiana, receives substantially all its feedstock from Cleveland-Cliffs’ facilities in Indiana Harbor and Burns Harbor via daily Norfolks Southern unit trains. Seen here is NS B09 loaded with steel coils returning to the Cleveland-Cliffs Tek and Kote facility, about 60 miles east of the Indiana Harbor Facility in East Chicago, Indiana. The Cleaveland Cliffs Indiana Harbor complex is one of the largest integrated steelmaking facilities in North America.
 
A coil of light gauge steel about 3500 ft usually weighs in up to 40,000 lbs. The coil steel units trains that supply the New Carlisle, IN are usually about 40 open coil cars with 3 to 5 coils per car depending and width and weight. I/N Tek performs continuous pickling and tandem rolling through the Continuous Descale Cold Mill (CDCM), and continuous annealing, temper rolling, and inspection through the Continuous Annealing Processing Line (CAPL) in order to provide material to I/N Kote for galvanizing or galvannealing. In the adjacent facility, I/N Kote, uses separate lines to produce 500,000 tons of hot-dip galvanized and galvannealed and 400,000 tons of electrogalvanized sheet annually. The principal are automotive and appliance markets.

New Carlisle Mill Yard
The entrance to the yard in New Carlisle, with a powered switch and powered derail under control of the Norfolk Southern dispatcher. A security fence is opened to allow the westbound out in the morning and the return at night.
 
The Cleveland-Cliffs Tek and Kote facility in New Carlisle, Indiana, receives substantially all its feedstock from Cleveland-Cliffs’ facilities in Indiana Harbor and Burns Harbor via daily Norfolk Southern unit trains. The trains run daily from New Carlisle to 60 miles west to the Indiana Harbor Facility in East Chicago, Indiana, and back again. The Cleveland Cliffs Indiana Harbor complex is one of the largest integrated steelmaking facilities in North America.
 
The plant in New Carlisle was built in 1990 as a joint venture between ArcelorMittal and Nippon Steel & Sumitomo Metal Corp. — then the world’s two largest steel companies. In 2019, Cleveland-Cliffs Inc. completed the acquisition of substantially all of the operations of ArcelorMittal USA LLC and its subsidiaries, forming the largest flat-rolled steel producer in North America. The Tek and Kote plant is now part of Cliffs.

Daily Coil Steel Delivery
Daily Norfolk Southern B09 unit trains deliver substrate from Indiana Harbor and Burns Harbor the Cleveland-Cliffs Tek and Kote facility in New Carlisle, Indiana.
 
Imagine what happens next. All of the coils you see will be welded into one continuous strip for processing. A massive buffer of steel ribbon in the fed mechanism allows time between coils to trim and weld the coils together are they are fed into the mill. The operation is a continuous, cold-rolling plant that produces sheet steel of unmatched quality and consistency. It enables the combination of five processes that take 12 days or more to perform via traditional batch methods. By welding coils end- to-end, the plant can run them continuously through these processes – pickling, tandem-rolling, annealing, temper-rolling and inspection – in less than a day.

Steel Coil Processing
Hot-rolled steel coils arrive from Cliffs Indiana Harbor Works in East Chicago on daily Norfolk Soutern unit trains. The coils are welded together into a continuous strip. The continuous steel strip fed into “Pickle” tanks of weak hydrochloric acid for cleaning. Tandem rollers exert tremendous pressure on the steel and squeeze the cold steel from strips 1/8-inch thick and a half-mile long into strips 2 miles long.
 
Tandem rolling also hardens the steel. After rolling, the steel is annealed - a heating, soaking and cooling treatment that makes steel easier for customers to reshape in their manufacturing operations. The traditional annealing once required six to seven days. At the New Carlisle facility annealing in a 10-minute process. The strip travels through a gas-fired, 10-story-high annealing furnace, then is rapidly cooled. The steel’s strength and metallurgical properties are computer-controlled during the operation.
 
The continuous strip is pickled again before passing through the temper mill where the steel is rolled to customer’s specifications. During the final step, the steel strip is inspected automatically for correct width and gauge and an antirust coating is applied. The processed steel is then recoiled and packaged, then stored in an automated coil storage facility to await shipping.

CoilSHIELD
Conrail CR 631402 Thrall 54’ “Coil Shield” Coil Car at I/N Tek facility (now Cliffs) in New Carlisle, Indiana circa 2020. The coil steel units trains that supply the New Carlisle, IN are usually about 40 open coil cars with 3 to 5 coils per car depending and width and weight. I/N Tek performs continuous pickling and tandem rolling through the Continuous Descale Cold Mill (CDCM), and continuous annealing, temper rolling, and inspection through the Continuous Annealing Processing Line (CAPL) in order to provide material to I/N Kote for galvanizing or galvannealing. In the adjacent facility, I/N Kote, uses separate lines to produce 500,000 tons of hot-dip galvanized and galvannealed and 400,000 tons of electrogalvanized sheet annually. The principal are automotive and appliance markets.

Crossing Over
Eastbound Norfolk Southern intermodal crossing over at CP448 on the NS Chicago Line. NS 9717 GE C44-9W intermodal  near New Carlisle on the Norfolk Southern Chicago Line. NS 4271 and NS 4398 are trailing, both rebuilt GE AC44C6M locomotives, rebuilt from Dash 9s in the DC to AC conversion program.
 
The Lake Shore and Michigan Southern Railway, established in 1833, was a major part of the New York Central Railroad’s Water Level Route from Buffalo, New York, to Chicago, Illinois, primarily along the south shore of Lake Erie and across northern Indiana.  In 1998, its ownership was split at Cleveland, Ohio, between CSX Transportation to the east and Norfolk Southern Railway in the west. Now from Cleveland, west to Chicago, the line is known as the Norfolk Southern Chicago Line.

Daily Departure
Each morning Norfolk Southern B09 (turn) unit train departs with empty open coil cars and gondolas filled with steel scrap for recycling taken in 2020. The train is passing over a powered derail that protects the mainline. Also note the dwarf signal across from the derail. NS 9552 is on point with NS 9320 trailing, both GE C44-94s. The locomotives are tail to tail because this train is a “turn”. When it reaches East Chicago, it will drop the empty coil cars, and pick up a train loaded with hot rolled coils to be taken back to New Carlisle.
